{[%evp 0,20,17,17,32,-11,-10,-11,12,28,29,23,19,20,19,19,20,34,28,31,51,17,17]
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {[#] Nimzo-Indian defence is the cornerstone
of the three-part repertoire for Black against 1.d4 (the other two parts being
the Catalan opening and the Ragozin defence). While there are several
reasonable alternatives for Black to White's 3.Nf3 and 3.g3, it is clear that
3...Bb4 is Black's best answer against 3.Nc3. It leads to complex and
strategically rich positions with plenty of room for creativity, despite being
heavily theoretically explored over the years. This makes it one of the most
popular opening systems for both colours. It is obvious from its name that the
famous Aron Nimzowitsch is credited with pioneering and developing this way of
defending with black pieces. However, it has to be said that other strong
players of his time have contributed to the early theory of the opening;
notably, Rubinstein with White, and Alekhine and Saemisch with both colours.
The key strategic premises of the Nimzo-Indian defence are quick development
and flexibility of central pawn structure. Black is ready to accept a
bishop-for-knight trade for this cause, giving White an opportunity to claim
the bishop pair advantage. However, Nimzowitsch demonstrated in his very first
games in this opening that Black can use the flexibility of his pawn structure
to set up a solid blockade in the centre and often limit white bishops this
way. The pair of black knights can then happily manoeuvre around the long pawn
chains, often facilitating Black's counter-attack on one of the flanks. Over
the years, this and many other strategic scenarios have been developed and
scrutinized in the Nimzo-Indian defence. White's action would prompt Black's
reaction, and vice versa. From a theoretical standpoint, The Nimzo-Indian has
therefore rarely been still. At the end of the day, one thing is certain -
Black is okay in the Nimzo! My goal in this opening database is to present the
most critical White's attempts to get an advantage against the Nimzo-Indian
and, logically, promising ways for Black to deal with these attempts. I have
covered the nine most sensible 4th moves for White. For the most popular ones:
4. e3, 4.Qc2, 4.Nf3, and 4.f3, I suggest not only one response for Black, but
rather two or (in case of 4.e3) even three responses. Just like in Catalan and
Ragozin databases, I present a 'solid' variation and a 'sharp' variation. The
idea is to have a flexible opening repertoire, which is a must in today's
competitive chess. The database is divided into 22 chapters: eight of them
cover 4.e3 variations; six cover 4.Qc2 variations; two cover 4.f3 variations;
while the other six 4th moves for White are condensed in one chapter each.
Finally, I should note that in the Ragozin database, some variations have been
cross-referenced to the corresponding ones in the Nimzo-Indian database. For
instance, 5.g3, 5.e3, and 5.Bd2 moves in the Ragozin transpose into 4.g3, 4.e3
and 4.Bd2 variations in the Nimzo-Indian database, respectively. Now, onto the
main course!} 4. e3 {The so-called Rubinstein variation is White's most
popular move against the Nimzo-Indian. White forgoes the option of developing
his dark-squared bishop to the most active g5-square (at least for the time
being) but keeps great flexibility with regard to the development of his other
pieces and potential central pawn structures.} ({While being slightly less
popular than 4.e3 by historical standards,} 4. Qc2 {[#] has been White's main
attempt to prove an edge in the Nimzo-Indian in modern times. Kasparov's
excellent results with it from 1988-2005 have prompted a serious theoretical
investigation in attempts to avoid the problems Black was facing in these
games. In recent years, several reliable ways of neutralizing White's
classical setup have been established, invariably connected to the
Ragozin-like d7-d5. Just like in 4.e3 variation, Black can castle first: 4...
0-0 and play 5...d5 next. However, the direct approach with} d5 {[#] (Noa
variation) is perhaps a tad more critical and demands very accurate play from
both sides. Even though this is my main recommendation for the solid
repertoire, positions arising from this setup can at times be quite imbalanced
and sharp. Still, this should not be a problem for a well-prepared black
player as it is often possible to equalize the game by forced means in this
variation.} ({On the other hand, my 'sharp' recommendation} 4... b6 $5 {
[#] usually has a less forced character and leaves more room for improvisation.
This is a good choice if you want to surprise your opponent or imbalance the
position strategically. The critical test of the variation is also the
principled move} 5. e4 ({The main alternative is the positional approach with} 
5. a3 {(5.Nf3 and 5.Bg5 lead to similar positions and are covered in the same
chapter)} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Bb7 7. Nf3 O-O {which will be covered extensively in
Chapter 14.}) {and after} 5... c5 {we get very interesting and atypical
positions that are covered in Chapter 13.}) {At this junction, White has two
main approaches. The first one is to win the bishop pair with} 5. a3 ({while
the second one is to play a Ragozin-like middlegame after} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
(6. Bf4 {is another way to develop the bishop, covered in Chapter 11 along
with other rare 6th move alternatives.}) 6... h6 7. Bh4 ({The main alternative
to the critical continuation 7.Bh4 is the positional} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. a3 Bxc3+
9. Qxc3 {which leads to Carlsbad structure type of positions that were
discussed in detail in the Ragozin database.}) 7... c5 8. dxc5 (8. Nf3 {
and other 8th move alternatives are covered in the same chapter.}) 8... g5 $5 {
This sharp approach (pioneered by GM Nigel Short) is the critical test of
White's opening philosophy. Kasparov had a lot of success against it back in
the day, but many improvements have been found for Black in the meantime. The
alternative is calmer 8...0-0 9.e3 Be6, followed by Nbd7, Rc8 and a solid IQP
position for Black.} 9. Bg3 Ne4 {[#] This is the tabiya of Short variation.
White has several options that branch into many sharp variations and
sub-variations. The most common one is} 10. e3 ({The alternatives} 10. Nf3) (
10. Bxb8) ({and} 10. O-O-O {are covered in Chapter 11.}) 10... Qa5 {After this
queen sortie, White has two main ways of defending the c3-knight:} 11. Nge2 ({
and} 11. Rc1) {Black continues in the Ragozin spirit with} 11... Bf5 {and the
following complications are analyzed in Chapter 12. Black does well in all
lines and in some of them he can easily take the initiative if White plays
inaccurately.}) 5... Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 O-O {[#] White has a wide choice of
possibilities at this point. The most common one is} 7. Nf3 ({while
alternatives:} 7. Bg5) (7. e3) ({and} 7. cxd5 {are all analyzed in Chapter 9.})
7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 b6 {[#] when we reach a position that has become the main
problem for White in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian recently. Thanks to his lead in
development, Black should be able to completely neutralize White's positional
trumps with precise play. You can find out how to do this in Chapter 10.}) ({
The third most common move for White in the Nimzo-Indian is the flexible} 4.
Nf3 {White reserves options to develop his pieces in several different ways,
depending on what Black does next. Of course, one can immediately realize that
by playing 4...d5, Black transposes into Ragozin defence, which was covered in
detail in the 'sister' opening database. This is a very solid and reliable
option, but what if you want to play something more complex? Then, I suggest
the familiar move:} b6 $5 {[#] I have suggested the queen's fianchetto
approach against 4.Qc2 variation as well. After this move, the game usually
obtains a less forced character while keeping some solidity and flexibility,
so it is a good choice if you want to mix things up. Now, White has many
continuations, including 5.e3 and 5.Qc2 that transpose into other chapters. In
Chapter 15, I explore independent options:} 5. Bg5 ({as well as} 5. Qb3) (5. g3
) ({and} 5. Bd2 Bb7 6. g3) 5... h6 6. Bh4 {and now the aggressive approach} g5
$5 7. Bg3 Ne4 {[#] that I also advocate in Chapters 11 and 12, seems like the
critical way to deal with the pin along the h4-d8 diagonal. The position
remains complex, but with a good outlook for Black.}) ({One of the most
interesting and direct attempts to fight the Nimzo-Indian is the so-called
Neo-Saemisch variation:} 4. f3 {[#] White shows, in no uncertain terms, that
he would like to build a strong pawn centre with e2-e4. The price that he is
paying for this ambitious plan is that he is taking away the most natural
square from his king's knight, just like in the Saemisch variation of the KID.
This slows down his development, sometimes to a high degree; however, White
gets other trumps in return and this variation should not be taken lightly by
Black by any means. For our Nimzo repertoire, I have thus prepared two
responses - a solid and a sharp one. The solid option, covered in Chapter 16,
is also the most natural move:} d5 ({The sharp alternative is} 4... c5 {
allowing White to achieve his goal in the centre after} 5. d5 O-O 6. e4 {
However, Black immediately strikes back at his centre with a flank diversion:}
b5 $5 {[#] This move introduces a Benoni-Benko hybrid type of position that
leads to fascinating double-edged play, making it a perfect choice for our
sharp repertoire. Details can be found in Chapter 17.}) {Now, White usually
wins the bishop pair under more favourable circumstances with:} 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6.
bxc3 {taking advantage of Black's inability to set up the dark-squared
blockade as in the Saemisch variation (4.a3). Black continues:} c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5
$5 {obtaining good piece counterplay against White's pawn centre. White has
several options at this point, but the main line runs:} 8. dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Ne7
10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3 Qc7 {[#] and we have another tabiya. Both sides have their
positional trumps and Black is usually successful in returning the sacrificed
pawn or obtaining compensation by other means (usually thanks to the ...b7-b6
break). This solid variation is analyzed in depth in Chapter 16.}) ({The
original Saemisch variation, covered in Chapter 18, is:} 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {
[#] which poses the main strategic test for Black in the Nimzo-Indian: can he
offset White's bishop pair with his own positional trumps (better pawn
structure, quicker development)? While White has some attacking potential in
this variation and is even ready to sacrifice his c4-pawn in many lines to
speed up the kingside attack, practice has shown that Black has a reliable way
to neutralize White's plan with:} c5 $1 6. e3 ({The main alternative} 6. f3 Nc6
7. e4 d6 {is covered in the same chapter.}) 6... Nc6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 b6 9. e4
{and now the key part of Black's strategy is the move} Ne8 $1 {avoiding the
unpleasant pin along the h4-d8 diagonal and preparing sorties such as ...
Ne8-d6 and ...f7-f5. After the usual:} 10. O-O Ba6 11. f4 f5 $1 {[#] Black
completes the strategy of blocking white bishops on both flanks, proving
Nimzowitsch right!}) ({The last four chapters feature somewhat less popular
variations, which can, nevertheless pose problems to Black if he is not
well-prepared or does not take them seriously. The first one is the
Nimzo-Catalan hybrid:} 4. g3 {when I would like to remain principled and
suggest the Ragozin-like:} d5 {Instead of exchanging the pawn on d5, White
usually sacrifices it for the sake of quick development and opening the
Catalan bishop. After} 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nf3 (6. a3 {is an interesting additional
option for White that has gained some popularity lately.}) 6... dxc4 7. O-O Nc6
{[#] we get a tabiya of this variation. White has several ways to prove
compensation for the pawn. Recently,} 8. Qa4 $5 {has gained quite a bit of
traction, with some strong GMs giving it a nod. It is backed by some tricky
tactical ideas and leads to a new and relatively uncharted territory.} ({
Two reasonable alternatives are:} 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. e3) ({and} 8. a3
Be7 9. e4) {Black should reply with:} 8... Nd5 9. Qc2 Be7 10. Rd1 {when we get
a complex position, examined in Chapter 19.}) ({Some 10-15 years ago, the
Leningrad variation:} 4. Bg5 {has been revived to a degree, but I believe that
the precise sequence:} c5 5. d5 d6 6. e3 exd5 7. cxd5 Nbd7 8. Bd3 (8. Bb5 {
is a safer alternative, though it does not promise much to White, either.})
8... Qa5 $1 9. Nge2 Nxd5 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 c4 $1 12. Bc2 O-O {[#] followed
by a few more precise moves, puts an end to White's hopes of getting anything
against the Nimzo-Indian playing Spassky's pet 4th move, as proven in Chapter
20.}) ({However, a more humble bishop move:} 4. Bd2 {may offer White more
chances to fight for an edge in the long run. My recommendation is to continue
like against the 4.e3 system:} O-O 5. e3 d5 6. Nf3 {and now:} b6 {[#] gives
Black a flexible setup. White has been doing well recently with the following
idea:} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Rc1 $5 Bb7 9. Bd3 {preparing the Pillsbury attack with
Nf3-e5, f2-f4, etc. Naturally, this is nothing to be scared of as Black has
his own trumps in such positions. In Chapter 21, I have analyzed two setups
for Black: a more solid one,} Be7 $5 ({and a somewhat sharper:} 9... a6 10. O-O
Bd6 11. Ne5 c5 12. f4 Nc6) 10. O-O Nbd7 {followed by ...c7-c5, etc.}) ({
Finally, we have the rarest of reasonable 4th moves:} 4. Qb3 {White's idea is
to provoke a certain concession from Black by attacking his bishop immediately.
Now, the principled reaction is:} c5 {and after} 5. dxc5 Nc6 $1 {is an
important move that temporarily sacrifices the pawn, but solves Black's
opening problems in all lines, as can be seen in Chapter 22.}) {In response, I
suggest that we start with the most flexible and popular move:} 4... O-O {
Now, White has several methods of development, of which the most common one is
the natural} 5. Bd3 ({The main alternative and Rubinstein's original treatment
of the 4.e3 variation is} 5. Nge2 {which will be covered in Chapter 1.
Alternatives, such as 5.Nf3, 5.a3 and 5.Bd2 usually transpose into other
chapters.}) 5... d5 {[#] The time has come for Black to show his cards in the
centre and this is the most orthodox way. White has several important setups
at this point.} 6. Nf3 {This is the most straightforward continuation that
leads to rather classical types of positions.} ({The first important
alternative is the 'improved Ne2 system':} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nge2 {[#] which is
covered in Chapter 2.}) ({The second one is immediate} 6. Nge2 {when Black can
continue just like in the main line:} dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 {
[#] with a typical IQP pawn structure, only with the knight on e2, instead on
f3. There are some important differences between these two setups, which I
will explain in Chapter 3.}) ({Finally, there is also} 6. a3 {which provokes
the trade of dark-squared bishop:} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 {Now, Black can not set up
the c5-b6 blockade against the c4-pawn, as we will study in Chapter 18:4.a3,
due to the tension between c4- and d5-pawns. However, Black has another good
setup at his disposal:} dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 {and now in case of both} 9. Nf3 ({and
} 9. Ne2) 9... Qc7 $1 {[#] is an important inclusion to determine the position
of the white light-squared bishop as soon as possible.}) 6... dxc4 $5 {I find
this move order to be the most accurate one to reach Karpov and Larsen
variations, my main recommendations against White's natural setup.} ({
Historically,} 6... c5 {has been the most common way to achieve that, but
recently White began exploring the option:} 7. cxd5 $5 ({instead of the main
line} 7. O-O) 7... exd5 8. dxc5 {when Black is the one with the IQP pawn. Now,
this is probably nothing special and Black should be fine even in those
positions, but I see no need to study this line since we can simply avoid it
with 6...dxc4 7.Bxc4 c5 move order.}) ({In addition to the main
recommendations after 6...dxc4, I also present a relatively new and
less-explored alternative:} 6... b6 7. O-O Ba6 $5 {[#] as an addition to the
repertoire. The idea is to utilize the flexibility of the Nimzo-Indian defence
in order to get a completely different type of position compared to those in
Karpov and Larsen variations. Black has some interesting strategic plots in
this rare system, that can help him to either outplay his opponent in the long
run or virtually equalize the game by force, as we will see in Chapter 8.}) 7.
Bxc4 c5 {Now, the exchange on d5 is not available any more and the majority of
white players simply continue} 8. O-O ({The only other note-worthy alternative
} 8. a3 {transposes into Chapter 4 after} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qc7) {At this point, I
have two recommendations for Black. My main, 'solid' recommendation is the
so-called Karpov variation:} 8... cxd4 {which leads to the IQP type of
position at once.} ({The second one is a bit more complex Larsen variation:} 
8... Nc6 9. a3 Ba5 $5 {[#] Black's idea in this system, which is covered in
Chapter 7, is to keep the central tension for as long as possible, thereby
preventing White from developing his bishop to g5, as in the Karpov variation.
This line has more 'sharpness' to it than the main line, although we sometimes
get the well-known IQP structure, nevertheless.}) 9. exd4 b6 {[#] This is the
'tabiya' of Karpov variation, which the ex-world champion successfully
employed for many years. Both sides have a wealth of development schemes at
their disposal. The main move is, naturally} 10. Bg5 ({Two main alternatives
are:} 10. Qe2 {followed by 11.Rd1;}) ({and} 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Bd3 {These two and
other 10th move alternatives will be analyzed in Chapter 5.}) 10... Bb7 {
In Chapter 6, we shall take a look at various possibilities for White and
Black in this interesting variation. The current state of theory is very
encouraging for Black.} *

