{[%evp 0,38,16,34,26,-9,0,-3,4,28,36,-14,24,31,35,30,8,-7,34,11,13,-5,-8,1,-7,
-8,-8,-8,8,1,12,1,0,0,0,5,6,10,2,27,26]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
O-O 5. Nge2 {[#] As I mentioned in the introduction, this was Rubinstein's
original treatment of the 4.e3 variation. Truth be told, he played 5.Bd3 and 5.
a3 in his first two games, but without much success, until he found a new
developing scheme where he temporarily blocks his light-squared bishop in
order to overprotect the c3 knight and induce the exchange on c3 without
having to weaken his pawn structure. These days, 5.Nge2 (or simply 5.Ne2 since
5.Nce2 is illegal!) is a reasonable variation that does not put an emphasis on
the opening, but rather offers chances for both sides to outplay the opponent
in a roughly equal, but complex middlegame. My suggestion is to continue:} Re8
$5 {This is a flexible move that vacates the f8-square for the bishop in case
of the usual a2-a3. It also leaves Black's options open with regard to the
pawn structure in the centre.} ({A more common and straightforward
continuation is} 5... d5 6. a3 Be7 ({or} 6... Bd6 7. c5 Be7) 7. cxd5 exd5 {
leading to a typical Carlsbad pawn structure. We can see that in both cases
Black bishop can be driven back to e7 (not an ideal square), which is one of
the reasons why Black got an idea to play 5...Re8.}) 6. a3 ({There is not much
point in ignoring the bishop in b4. For example,} 6. g3 d5 7. cxd5 $6 Qxd5 $1 {
uses exactly the fact that the c3-knight is pinned, so Black takes the
initiative early:} 8. Rg1 Qh5 (8... e5 $5 $36 {looks like an excellent version
of the Chigorin-defense for Black.}) 9. h3 e5 10. g4 Qh4 11. Bg2 Nc6 12. d5 Ne7
$15 {1-0 (37) Bluvshtein,M (2558)-Onischuk,A (2699) Montreal 2009}) (6. Ng3 d5
7. Bd2 {was a creative idea of GM Fedoseev} (7. Be2 b6 8. O-O Bb7 $13 {
transposes to 6.a3 Bf8 7.Ng3 variation}) {and now} 7... b6 $5 $146 {is a
possible improvement} ({over the game:} 7... c5 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxd4 10.
Qxd4 e5 11. Qd2 $13 {1/2-1/2 (66) Fedoseev,V (2713)-Van Foreest,J (2617)
Hoogeveen NED 2018}) 8. Rc1 Ba6 $13 {with a hybrid of Chapter 8 and 21.} (8...
Bf8 $5 $13)) 6... Bf8 {[#] The bishop is tucked away on f8, where it is not in
the way of other black pieces. Mission accomplished.} ({Of course, it would be
pointless to play:} 6... Bxc3+ $6 7. Nxc3 $14 {which would make Rubinstein
very happy and give White an automatic positional advantage.}) {This is the
first important crossroad for White. He has plenty of options to complete his
development and try to claim as much ground in the centre as possible. The
most popular one is} 7. Ng3 {which is indeed the simplest move available.} ({
The most serious alternative is space-gaining:} 7. d5 {Now, I would like to
recommend} a5 $5 {which prepares the manoeuvre of the knight to the juicy
outpost on c5.} (7... d6 {is a serious alternative, although the pawn
structure that arises from} 8. dxe6 $5 fxe6 {is a bit weird. Let us keep it
classical.}) 8. Ng3 ({The other development scheme is} 8. g3 Na6 9. Bg2 Nc5 {
[#] However, White already starts to feel some annoyance with his weak light
squares. Black has a positional threat ...a5-a4.} 10. b3 ({White could also
ignore Black's positional threat and just play} 10. O-O {After:} a4 11. Qc2 d6
{the knight has a perfect outpost on c5 and Black has no problems whatsoever.}
12. Bd2 (12. e4 {somehow does not seem in the spirit of the position as it
shuts down the g2-bishop and weakens the dark-squares complex.} Bd7 (12... Ng4
$5) 13. h3 Nb3 14. Rb1 Nxc1 15. Nxc1 h5 16. dxe6 Bxe6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (48) Ladva,
O (2337)-Yemelin,V (2558) Tallinn 2014}) 12... Bd7 ({In addition, Black has a
cool pawn sacrifice:} 12... c6 $1 $146 13. dxc6 Qb6 14. cxb7 Bxb7 $36 {with
complete domination on the light squares and upcoming pressure against b2- and
c4- pawns.}) 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. Nd5 c6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Nd4 Bd7 $13 {1/2-1/2 
(41) Dubov,D (2638)-Jakovenko,D (2713) Ekaterinburg 2013}) 10... exd5 11. cxd5
b6 $1 {The key idea. Black develops his light-squared bishop with a strong
effect.} 12. O-O (12. d6 $2 {would be a bad idea since this pawn would be
doomed after} c6 $17) 12... Ba6 {[#] Once again, Black has emerged in a good
shape out of the opening. He has managed to minimize the impact of White's
space advantage by finding the best squares for his pieces. Moreover, White is
the one who still needs to find the way to organize his troops harmoniously,
since the desired Ne2-d4 is not an option. The following games show some of
his struggles:} 13. Ra2 (13. a4 Nfe4 (13... Rc8 $5) 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qc2 Nc5
16. Re1 Qf6 17. Bb2 {1/2-1/2 (31) Steingrimsson,H (2530)-Grandelius,N (2569)
Reykjavik 2014} Qg6 $1 {targeting the b3-weakness.} 18. Qxg6 hxg6 $15) (13. Bb2
Nd3 14. Qc2 Ng4 (14... Bc5 $5 {stopping Ne2-d4 deserved serious attention.} 15.
Na4 Nxb2 16. Nxc5 bxc5 17. Qxb2 d6 $15) 15. h3 Nge5 16. Rfd1 Qf6 17. Nd4 Nxb2
18. Qxb2 c5 19. dxc6 dxc6 $13 {1/2-1/2 (47) Mendonca,L (2350)-Martinovic,S 
(2554) Zadar CRO 2018}) 13... Nfe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Rc2 (15. Bb2 $6 {looks
bad for White.} Qg5 $1 $36 16. Bxe4 Rxe4 17. Nc3 Ree8 $17 {0-1 (42) Breukelman,
J (2325)-Zelbel,P (2445) Vlissingen 2016}) 15... Nc5 (15... a4 $5 $146 16. b4
c5 $132 {is a dynamic option that looks quite promising for Black.}) 16. Rd2 a4
17. b4 Nb3 $132 {1/2-1/2 (45) Deglmann,L (2349)-Sadilek,P (2277) Austria 2013})
8... Na6 {[#]} 9. Be2 (9. Bd3 Nc5 10. Bc2 {seems to solve the problem of
b3-square, but creates another one:} exd5 11. cxd5 b5 $1 {An excellent gambit.}
12. Nxb5 (12. O-O Bb7 $15) 12... Ba6 13. Nc3 Bd6 $1 {Black bishops are showing
their potential.} 14. b4 Be5 {White is under a very strong pressure and
relatively the best was} 15. Qd2 (15. Bb2 $2 {1/2-1/2 (95) Badelka,O (2175)
-Drakoulakos,G (2270) Poprad 2016 should have lost the game to} Rb8 $1 $19)
15... Nb7 16. b5 Bxb5 17. Rb1 Ba6 18. Nce2 Nc5 $15) (9. Rb1 exd5 10. cxd5 c6
11. Be2 b5 12. dxc6 dxc6 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 $15 {1/2-1/2 (14) Berezjuk,S (2430)
-Markos,J (2467) Czechia 2002}) 9... Nc5 10. b3 ({Again,} 10. O-O {allows} a4 {
with a good position for Black.} 11. e4 (11. Rb1 d6 12. Qc2 g6 $1 {The bishop
finds new employment on the long diagonal.} 13. f3 Nb3 14. e4 Nxc1 15. Qxc1 Bg7
$15 {0-1 (64) Simeonidis,I (2275)-Oleksienko,M (2588) Kavala 2008}) {Here, I
like GM Wojtaszek's pawn sacrifice very much:} 11... Nb3 $5 12. Rb1 Nxc1 13.
Rxc1 d6 14. Nxa4 exd5 15. exd5 g6 16. Nc3 h5 {The a-pawn was not so important
