{[%evp 0,41,19,25,23,8,0,-4,23,28,26,28,27,14,26,9,24,10,31,35,49,43,38,19,31,
-5,-5,-8,-7,-8,10,3,-5,21,27,25,0,-8,10,10,47,50,161,183]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nge2 {[#] This system has
become fashionable in the recent 3-4 years. White's plan with the early
exchange on d5 and knight's development to e2 is to execute Botvinnik's plan
f2-f3, e3-e4. This plan is known to work well for White in two opening
variations: 1. Exchange variation of QGD and 2. Saemisch variation of the
Nimzo-Indian where black plays d5. In comparison, this is a better version of
this type of position for Black for two reasons: 1. white bishop is on c1 and
not on g5 as in the QGD; and 2. Black has not traded his dark-squared bishop
on c3 yet, as in Saemisch variation. Thus, Black is doing well from a
strategic point of view. Nevertheless, this variation leads to a complex fight
in the middlegame, where the knowledge of typical manoeuvres and positions
plays a much larger role than move-by-move theoretical knowledge. For that
reason, I will try to present several typical plans for both sides at each
important junction. Naturally, Black starts with} Re8 {which is a generally
useful move in these positions, as we have seen in Chapter 1.} 8. Bd2 {White
has recently preferred this move, in connection with Rc1, over castling -
similar to Chapter 21. This is definitely a useful inclusion for White as he
fights against Black's ...c7-c5 break.} (8. O-O {is the other option, when
White may or may not play Bd2, Rc1 plan later. Now, just like in the main line,
I analyze two possible bishop retreats. The bishop will not take on c3, so
there is no need for it to linger on b4 any more, especially since Black wants
to play ...c7-c5 at some point.} Bd6 {This is a more active retreat.} ({
An equivalent alternative is} 8... Bf8 {[#]} 9. a3 (9. Qc2 a5 10. Bd2 Na6 11.
a3 c6 12. Rad1 g6 {and we have a manoeuvring game:} 13. Bc1 Nc7 14. Rfe1 Ne6
15. Qb1 b5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (43) Aleksandrov,A (2619)-Georgiev,K (2650) Germany
2000}) (9. f3 {is typically answered with:} c5 10. Qe1 b6 11. Qh4 {This is a
standard manoeuvre in this variation. White sets up some vague attacking
threats on the kingside...} Ba6 $1 {...but this trade dispels his hopes.} 12.
Bxa6 Nxa6 13. a3 Nc7 14. Kh1 Be7 15. Qf2 Ne6 $15 {0-1 (48) Strand,K (2445)
-Olofsson,D (2485) Denmark 1997}) 9... a5 10. Kh1 {A wise waiting move.} Na6
11. f3 c5 {Leko's reaction is principled, although one should note how Kramnik
waited for him to play Na6 before he pushed f2-f3. Now the knight cannot reach
the best c6-square any more.} 12. Nf4 Nc7 13. dxc5 $5 {Opening of the centre
will favour White, who has slightly more active pieces, but Black managed to
equalize eventually without many problems.} Bxc5 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16.
Bxe4 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 {1/2 (35) Kramnik,V (2802)-Leko,P (2730) Dortmund 2001} Ne6
$11) 9. Ng3 {This is a more patient plan,} ({compared to} 9. f3 {which allows
the immediate:} c5 {when the knight can put pressure on white centre from c6.}
10. Nb5 (10. Qe1 Nc6 11. Qh4 Be7 12. Qf2 a6 13. g4 b5 {Both sides expand on
the flank where they have an advantage in numbers. The position becomes
double-edged.} 14. Ng3 b4 15. Nce2 a5 16. g5 Nd7 17. f4 Ba6 {This exchange, as
we have already seen many times, is very useful for Black.} 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 $13 {
0-1 (41) Giorgadze,G (2580)-Almasi,Z (2655) Yerevan 1996}) 10... Bf8 11. dxc5
Bxc5 12. Nbd4 Nc6 {[#] We can safely say that Black has equalized. The
backward e-pawn is just as important positional trait as the isolated one on
d5. Below are two sample games which prove that Black has an easy game:} 13.
Kh1 (13. Bd2 Qb6 $1 14. Kh1 Nxd4 15. exd4 Bxd4 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 17. Bc3 Qf4 18.
Bb5 Rd8 19. Re1 d4 $15 {1/2 (89) Gelfand,B (2736)-Carlsen,M (2714) Moscow 2007}
) 13... Ne5 14. b3 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 a5 $1 16. Ng3 b6 17. Rd1 Qe7 18. Qd2 h5 $1 {
Black uses his rook's pawns very effectively.} 19. Qf2 h4 20. Nge2 Nh5 $15 {
1/2 (38) Xiu Deshun (2534)-Yu Yangyi (2675) Xinghua CHN 2013}) 9... c6 10. Bd2
Nbd7 {The knight is manoeuvred to a flexible post on f8, just like in the
Queen's gambit.} 11. Rc1 Nf8 12. f3 Ne6 {[#] White directed all his forces
toward the e4-square, but there is no piece defending the d4-pawn. This slows
down his ambitious central push.} 13. Be1 (13. Kh1 a6 14. Be1 Bf8 15. Bf2 c5
16. dxc5 {This is a different reaction compared to Eljanov's game. White wants
to open the centre 'a la Kramnik'.} Nxc5 17. Bb1 b6 18. e4 dxe4 19. Ncxe4 Nfxe4
20. Nxe4 {1/2-1/2 (65) Abdusattorov,N (2558) -Iordachescu,V (2591) Batumi 2018}
Bf5 $11) 13... a6 14. Bf2 {A typical way to give support to the d4-pawn, but
Black is just in time with central counterplay:} c5 $1 15. Re1 cxd4 16. exd4
Nf4 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Bb1 Bd7 19. Qd2 g6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (67) Eljanov,P (2759)
-Hou,Y (2651) Sharjah 2017}) 8... Bd6 {It is not easy to tell which bishop
retreat is better - they both look pretty good. This one is apparently more
active, but it is also more difficult to push ...c7-c5 with the bishop here.} (
{On the other hand, the bishop is not in the way of other pieces after} 8...
Bf8 9. O-O {and now} b6 {is the best way to prepare ...c7-c5.} ({However,} 9...
a5 $5 10. Rc1 Na6 {[#] deserves an honourable mention, supporting ...c7-c5
with pieces.} 11. f3 ({It may be more prudent to spend a move on} 11. a3 c6 12.
f3 c5 {Black does not mind wasting a tempo to prevent the e3-e4 break.} 13. Qe1
Bd7 14. Qh4 h6 $13 15. dxc5 $6 Nxc5 16. Bc2 b5 $1 $132 {Just in time with
queenside counterplay.} 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 Na4 19. Qd4 Nb6 20. e4 Nc4 $1 $15
{0-1 (31) Sorm,D (2314)-Balogh,C (2632) Czech Republic 2017}) {Now Black can
improve his knight's position with} 11... Nb4 $5 {planning to return to c6
after ...c7-c5.} 12. Bb1 c5 {At this point, White has two typical attacking
plans at his disposal:} 13. g4 ({and} 13. Qe1 b6 14. a3 Nc6 15. Qh4 Ba6 16.
Rfe1 g6 17. Rcd1 Rc8 $13 {1/2-1/2 (44) Dambacher, M (2425)-Naiditsch,A (2664)
Netherlands 2006}) 13... b6 14. a3 Nc6 15. Rf2 Ba6 16. Rg2 g6 $13 {1/2 (34)
Rakhmanov,A (2570)-Zakhartsov,V (2586) Voronezh 2010 CBM 137 [Zakhartsov]}) 10.
Rc1 (10. Qc2 {is less appealing because Black can develop more actively:} c5
11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Nf4 Nc6 $11 {using the inferior position of the queen to win
a tempo thanks to the ...Nc6-b4 threat.} 13. Bb5 Bb7 14. Na4 Rc8 $1 15. Rfd1 a6
16. Bf1 Ne5 17. Be1 Qc7 18. Rac1 Ng6 19. Nxg6 hxg6 20. h3 Bd6 $15 {1/2-1/2
Kacheishvili,G (2505)-Dizdar,G (2550)/Pula 1997/ (37)}) 10... Bb7 {[#] White
has several setups at his disposal. Recently,} 11. Nf4 {followed by Qd1-f3,
gained the attention of strong players because it still gives Black some
opening problems to solve due to the pressure against d5-pawn.} ({Black is
very well-positioned against the typical} 11. f3 {and after} c5 12. Qe1 Nbd7
13. Qf2 a6 14. Kh1 g6 $13 {he could be satisfied with opening results.} 15. Bb1
Bg7 16. Nf4 Rc8 17. Nd3 h5 18. Nf4 Nf8 19. a3 Qd6 20. Ba2 c4 21. Bb1 b5 $132 {
0-1 Gavrish,L (2212)-Ter Sahakyan,S (2617)/Yerevan 2016/CBM 173 Extra (37)})
11... c5 12. Qf3 {[#]} (12. dxc5 $6 {is premature due to} bxc5 13. Qf3 Nbd7 $1
{and now ...Nd7-e5 is coming either way.} 14. Qh3 Ne5 15. Bb5 Bc8 16. Qg3 Bd7
17. Bxd7 Qxd7 $15 {0-1 (53) Laciner,K (2297)-Atalik,E (2448) Konya 2012}) {
This is an important position. Black is apparently facing some difficulties
completing his development due to the pressure against the central pawn. If
one is not familiar with this position, it is very easy to end up in an
inferior position. However, we shall see that Black has several playable
continuations at his disposal, as well as one that forces simplifications:}
12... Nc6 $5 {Black temporarily sacrifices the central pawn, but he will get
back material with a roughly equal endgame.} ({Karjakin's} 12... Na6 {failed
to impress from a theoretical standpoint:} 13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. exd4 $14 Nc7 15.
Bc2 Bd6 16. Be3 Ne4 17. Ba4 Re7 18. Bb3 Qd7 19. h3 Nxc3 20. bxc3 Bc6 21. Nh5
Re6 22. Bc2 Ba4 $132 {1-0 Carlsen,M (2832)-Karjakin,S (2781)/ Stavanger NOR
2017/The Week in Chess 1180 (44)}) ({And neither did Lenic's:} 12... Ne4 {
leave a better impression after} 13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. exd4 Nxd2 15. Rxd2 $14 {
1/2-1/2 Geirnaert,S (2449)-Lenic,L (2625)/Reykjavik 2015/CBM 170 (90)}) ({
However, I quite like the idea that Grigoriants used in the following game:} 
12... a6 $5 13. Rfd1 Ra7 $1 {Protecting the bishop and planning for the rook
to join the game via the seventh rank.} 14. Bb1 Bc6 15. Nce2 Rd7 16. Ng3 g6 17.
Nd3 Bb7 18. Ne5 Rd6 19. Bc3 Rde6 20. Ne2 Bg7 21. Nd3 R6e7 $13 {1/2-1/2 (30)
Swayams,M (2432)-Grigoriants,S (2568) Caleta 2018}) ({I can also suggest a new
move:} 12... Bc6 $5 $146 13. b3 (13. Rfd1 c4 $15) 13... a6 14. Qh3 g6 $13 {
with a compex struggle.}) 13. Ncxd5 ({Another way to win the d-pawn is:} 13.
Nh5 Nxh5 14. Qxh5 g6 15. Qxd5 {but it poses no problems to Black after} cxd4 ({
or} 15... Qh4 $5 $44) 16. exd4 Nb4 17. Qxd8 Rexd8 $11 18. Be4 Bxe4 19. Nxe4
Nxa2 20. Rc7 Rxd4 21. Nf6+ Kg7 22. Be3 Ra4 23. b3 Rb4 24. Nd5 Re4 25. Ra1 Nb4
26. Nxb6 $11 {1/2-1/2 Wemmers,X (2348)-Muzychuk,A (2566)/Caleta 2014/CBM 159 
(32)}) 13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Ne5 $1 {This is the tactical point.} 15. dxe5 Qxd5
16. Qxd5 Bxd5 {[#] Two pawns are hanging and White can not protect them both.
Drawing margin is quite big in the arising endgame, whichever pawn White
decides to keep.} 17. Bc3 (17. b3 Rxe5 18. Bc3 Ree8 19. Bb5 Red8 20. Rfd1 a6
21. Be2 Be6 22. e4 b5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (40) Shtembuliak,E (2501)-Friedel,J (2561)
Merida 2017}) 17... Bxa2 18. Be4 Rab8 19. Ra1 Bc4 20. Rfd1 a5 $11 {½-½
Martinovic,S (2552)-Saric,A (2544)/Mali Losinj CRO 2017/ (62)}) 9. Rc1 ({
As discussed earlier,} 9. Qc2 {is not an ideal square for the queen due to Na 
(c)6-b4 threat.} Na6 $5 10. a3 {It makes little sense for White to give up his
strongest minor piece for a knight on the rim.} c5 11. Bb5 (11. O-O c4 12. Bf5
b5 $1 13. Nxb5 Bxf5 14. Qxf5 Bxh2+ 15. Kxh2 Qb8+ 16. Kg1 Qxb5 17. Rab1 Rab8 $11
{1-0 (22) Napalkov,V (2466)-Kitson,K (2532) ICCF email 2004}) 11... Bd7 12.
Bxd7 Qxd7 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. O-O Rac8 $11 {0-1 (46) Agdestein,S (2586)-Ghosh,D 
(2556) chess.com INT 2018}) 9... a6 {I prefer this way of preventing Nc3-b5 to
9...c6, since it is important to keep the option of playing ...c7-c5 at the
right moment.} 10. O-O Nbd7 {[#] White is at a crossroads - he has three ways
to start his kingside expansion:} 11. Nf4 (11. Ng3 Nf8 ({In the game ½-½ (34)
Martinovic, S (2537)-Palac, M (2554) Porec 2014, Black decided to tolerate the
knight on f5 by playing:} 11... b6 12. Nf5 Bf8 13. Qf3 Bb7 {However, after} 14.
Qh3 {his position was somewhat uncomfortable.}) {Now, in case of} 12. Nf5 {
Black swaps it off:} (12. Nce2 {allows Black to equalize comfortably with} Ne4
$11 13. Be1 c6 14. a4 Nxg3 15. Nxg3 a5 16. Qb3 g6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (50) Yu Yangyi 
(2765)-Leko,P (2690) Porto Carras GRE 2018}) (12. f3 {is answered, as usual,
with} c5) 12... Bxf5 13. Bxf5 {and the position after:} c6 14. f3 Ne6 15. Be1
c5 16. Kh1 cxd4 17. exd4 Bf4 18. Bd2 Qd6 $11 {was balanced in Navara,D (2739)
-Kryvoruchko,Y (2714) Chartres 2017 ½-½ (52)}) ({and} 11. f3 c5 12. Bb1 b5
13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nd4 {1/2-1/2 (55) Rakhmanov,A (2620)-Van Wely,L (2654)
Linares 2015 and now} Qb6 $5 $146 15. Nce2 b4 $132 {looks pretty good for
Black, with ...a5, Ba6 and ...Ne5 coming.}) 11... c6 {[#] I believe that White
should prevent ...Nf6-e4, Nd7-f6 maneuver in this position. Thus,} 12. f3 {
makes the most sense.} (12. h3 {is the most recent try on a grandmaster level,
but it failed to impress:} Nf8 (12... Ne4 $5 {as in Jakovenko's game below} 13.
Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bc4 Nf6 {was also quite sensible.}) 13. Nh5 Ne4 (13... Nxh5 $5
14. Qxh5 g6 15. Qd1 Ne6 $15) 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bc4 g6 16. Ng3 Be6 17. Nxe4 Bxc4
18. Nxd6 Bxf1 19. Nxe8 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Qxe8 $15 {1/2-1/2 (103) Lagarde,M (2604)
-Cheparinov,I (2691) Caleta ENG 2019}) (12. Re1 {is a bit pointless,
especially in the view of Black's reply:} Ne4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bb1 Nf6 15. a3
Bg4 16. f3 Bf5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (40) Valsecchi,A (2508)-Jakovenko,D (2710) Antalya
2017}) (12. Qf3 {prevents the above-mentioned knight maneuver, but the queen
is not placed particularly well on f3.} Nf8 13. h3 Ng6 (13... Ne6 $5 14. Nxe6
Bxe6 $15) 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Rfe1 Bc7 $15 {0-1 (40) Cervantes Landeiro,T (2087)
-Pierrot,J (2392) Montevideo 2018}) 12... Nf8 13. Kh1 Ng6 14. Nce2 Qb6 15. b3 {
So far, so good, although I would like to suggest a possible improvement here:}
c5 $5 $146 {with the idea to strike back in the center while Black still has a
chance to do it.} ({The game Fressinet,L (2645)-Gharamian,T (2614) Nimes 2018
½-½ (62) continued:} 15... Bd7 16. g4 $1 Nxf4 17. exf4 Re7 18. Qc2 Rae8 19.
Ng3 $13 {and even though all of this looks natural for Black and the engine
approves of his moves, the position looks a bit static and unpleasant to play
without the possibility to open up the centre with ...c6-c5.}) {Possible
variations are:} 16. Bxg6 ({as well as:} 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Bc3 c4 (17... Rxe3
$6 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. b4 $1 Bxb4 20. Bd4 $14) 18. bxc4 dxc4 19. Bxc4 Rxe3 $13) (
{and:} 16. Bc3 c4 17. bxc4 dxc4 18. Bxc4 Rxe3 $13) 16... hxg6 17. Bc3 c4 $1 {
This is the key motif for counterplay in most lines.} 18. bxc4 dxc4 19. e4 g5
20. Nh3 $13 {with a very interesting position full of play for both sides.} *

