{[%evp 0,50,19,31,14,-14,-11,-4,30,28,29,26,26,16,-7,2,21,9,14,18,9,18,14,1,18,
-26,0,-36,32,-12,-13,-149,-142,-191,-186,-186,-190,-377,-360,-361,-361,-604,
-602,-647,-349,-493,-500,-514,-519,-718,-739,-29993,-29994]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nge2 {[#] A more modest development of the
knight than customary Nf3 - but it has some hidden points, as we will see soon.
} dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 {With his last two moves, Black is aiming for the IQP type
of position.} 8. O-O ({White could take advantage of Black's last move by
taking the bishop pair advantage with} 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 ({The other
recapture} 9. bxc3 {[%emt 0:00:04] will be discussed in Chapter}) 9... cxd4 10.
exd4 Nc6 11. Be3 b6 12. O-O Bb7 $11 {[#] After natural developing moves from
both sides, we have reached a position that can also arise from a variation of
4.e3 c5 5.Nge2 Nimzo-Indian, only in this case Black has an extra tempo
compared to that line because White has wasted one move here, going Bd3-Bxc4.
Thus, White has no time to play a very important move 13.Qf3 here and we can
say that Black is fine. Below are some examples that prove this:} 13. Ba2 {
Preparing 14.Qf3...} ({Alternatives are:} 13. Qd3 Rc8 14. Rad1 h6 15. Ba2 Ne7
16. f3 Bd5 ({I would actually prefer:} 16... Nf5 $5 17. Bf2 Nd5) 17. Nxd5 Nexd5
18. Bf2 Qc7 19. Bb3 Rfd8 $11 {0-1 (35) Gruenberg,H (2455)-Enders,P (2365)
Dresden 1985}) ({and:} 13. Rc1 h6 14. Ba2 Ne7 15. Bf4 Nfd5 {Black achieved a
full blockade of the isolated pawn.} 16. Be5 Nf5 17. Re1 Nxc3 18. Rxc3 Qg5 19.
f3 Rac8 $15 {1/2-1/2 (70) Anuszkiewicz,K (2257)-Staniszewski,P (2451) Glogow
2001}) 13... Ne7 $1 {...but it will not happen. We will see this knight
manoeuvre in several other positions in the 4.e3 variation.} 14. Bg5 Ng6 15. d5
{This looks like a good way to get rid of the isolated pawn, but things are
not so simple for White even here.} ({Perhaps White should look in another
direction:} 15. h4 $5 $146 h6 16. h5 Ne7 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Qd2 {although after:
} Kh7 19. d5 Rg8 $1 20. Rad1 f5 $132 {Black has interesting counterplay down
the g-file.}) 15... h6 $1 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. dxe6 fxe6 {[#] Structurally
speaking, White should be better. However, Black's kingside activity related
to g2-square more than compensates for the isolated pawn.} 18. Qg4 (18. Qd7
Bxg2 $1 {is the tactical point.} 19. Qxe6+ Qxe6 20. Bxe6+ Kh7 21. Kxg2 Nf4+ 22.
Kg3 Nxe6 $15) 18... Nf4 19. g3 Qg6 20. h3 Qxg4 21. hxg4 Nh3+ 22. Kh2 Rxf2+ 23.
Rxf2 Nxf2 24. Bxe6+ Kh8 $15 {0-1 (40) Melas,R (2165)-Cvitan,O (2516)/Rijeka
2009/CBM 132 Extra}) 8... cxd4 9. exd4 {[#]} ({White can also play} 9. Nxd4 {
although this is rather tame and Black has many good ways to continue. For
example:} a6 10. Qb3 (10. Be2 e5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (17) Giorgadze,G-Portisch,L 
(2585) Kropotkin 1995}) 10... Be7 (10... Bd6 $5 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. h3 Nbd7) 11.
Rd1 Qc7 12. a4 Bd7 13. Bd2 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 $15 {0-1 (60) Cuartas,C (2330)
-Greenfeld,A (2470) Thessaloniki 1984}) {Let us stop for a moment and consider
why White would play this IQP position with the knight on e2 instead of the
more natural square f3. There are several important differences. First, the
knight on e2 does not obstruct the third rank for a manoeuvre of a heavy piece
(usually the queen) toward one of g3 or h3 squares. Secondly, the knight can
sometimes join the fight for the key d5-square via f4, which is not possible
when it is on f3. Thirdly, although this is already a much less common
scenario, the knight on e2 does not obstruct the f2-f4-f5 push. Finally, and
this is already a fine point, the knight is somewhat better positioned on e2
than f3 for defensive purposes as it overprotects both c3 and d4, while also
not being in the line of attack of black b7-bishop. Therefore, this can be a
tricky IQP setup and Black needs to exercise caution. He has two reasonable
continuations:} 9... Nc6 ({and} 9... Nbd7 {[#] Black's idea in this line is to
develop with: ...Nd7-b6 and ... Bc8-d7-c6, taking full control over the
d5-square. White has many options, but I believe that Rakhmanov's queen-lift:}
10. Qd3 {gives him the best chances.} (10. Bg5 {is an automatic move, though
it may not be the most accurate here. After:} Be7 11. Qd3 Nb6 12. Bb3 Bd7 {
[#] White usually sets up the typical diagonal battery with:} 13. Bc2 ({
The alternative is a somewhat speculative pawn sacrifice:} 13. Nf4 Bc6 14. Qg3
$5 Qxd4 15. Rad1 (15. Rae1 $5 $44) 15... Qc5 16. Rfe1 Rfd8 17. Nd3 Qf5 18. Re5
Qg4 19. Qxg4 Nxg4 20. Bxe7 Rxd3 21. Rxd3 Nxe5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (44) Blokhuis,E-De
Boer,G (2385) Eindhoven 1988}) (13. Rad1 Bc6 14. Rfe1 {was too tentative in
Balashov,Y (2477)-Aleksandrov,A (2637) Izhevsk 2013, 0-1 (80) and Black
achieved all that he wanted after:} Re8 15. Qh3 Nbd5 16. Nf4 h6 17. Nfxd5 Nxd5
18. Bd2 Rc8 19. Bc2 Bg5 $15) 13... g6 14. Bb3 {It is well-known in Panov
attack/IQP middlegames that the bishop should switch the diagonal once it has
provoked weakening with ...g7-g6.} ({White did not get this point in the game
Kalashian, L-Gipslis, A Moscow 1959, 0-1 (50) and he got into a worse position
after:} 14. Rad1 Bc6 15. Qh3 Nbd5 16. Qh4 Re8 17. Bb1 $6 Nh5 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19.
