{[%evp 0,19,19,25,23,8,0,6,33,25,21,23,26,26,16,26,38,20,50,45,57,12]} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O cxd4
9. exd4 b6 {[#] Karpov variation is one of the most reliable and time-tested
systems against White's main setup in the Rubinstein Nimzo-Indian. Even though
the strong Hungarian grandmaster Lajos Portisch has employed it several times
before Karpov, it was the ex-world champion who put the variation into
prominence in the 1970ies, scoring excellently with black pieces. Black's idea
is to develop the bishop on the long diagonal as quickly as possible, keeping
options to capture on c3 with the other bishop or retreat it to e7, depending
on circumstances. He also enjoys some flexibility regarding the development of
the other knight because Nc6 and Nbd7 are both viable setups. White also has a
variety of plans, which makes this variation quite popular for both sides. The
most natural continuation is 10.Bg5 and we will deal with it in the next
chapter. In this one, we will look at the most important 10th move
alternatives for White.} 10. Qe2 {With this move, White plans to support the
d4-pawn with 11.Rd1.} ({Another important setup for White is} 10. Re1 {(a
different move order to reach the same position is 10.Bd3 Bb7 11.Re1)} Bb7 11.
Bd3 ({On a side note,} 11. a3 $6 {is just as problematic as on the 10th move.
After:} Bxc3 12. bxc3 Qc7 {White faces problems with the c3-pawn.} 13. Qe2 (13.
Bd3 {is a speculative pawn sacrifice that does not work if Black plays
accurately.} Qxc3 14. Bg5 Nbd7 15. Ne5 ({or} 15. Re3 Qc6 16. Rc1 Qd5 $17 {
0-1 (26) Aagaard,J (2522)-Akopian,V (2681) Porto Carras GRE 2011}) 15... Nxe5
$1 16. dxe5 Rfd8 {[#] This is a typical tactical idea in Karpov variation.
Black ignores the threat to f6-knight and his dark squares and starts his own
play.} 17. Re3 (17. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 $17) (17. exf6 Rxd3 18. Qg4 Qd4 $15) 17... Be4
$1 18. Bxe4 (18. exf6 Rxd3 19. Rxd3 Qxd3 $15) 18... Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Nxe4 $8 (
19... Qxe3 $4 20. Bxa8 $1 $18 {was the last trick.}) 20. Rxc3 Nxc3 21. Rd7 h6
22. Bd2 Nd5 $17 {Sanal,V-Kuljasevic,D/ICC blitz, 2017 (48) 0-1}) 13... Nbd7 14.
Nd2 Bd5 {Black trades off light-squared bishops and takes control of the
square complex of the same color.} 15. Bb2 Bxc4 16. Nxc4 Nd5 17. Rac1 b5 $15 {
0-1 (72) Meskovs,N (2438)-Van Wely,L (2684) Riga LAT 2014}) 11... Nbd7 {
This is the most usual continuation and I do believe that the knight is placed
better on d7 than c6 in this particular variation. However, in order to
appreciate why this is the case, we should also take a look at 11...Nc6.} (
11... Nc6 12. a3 Be7 {The bishop retreat has historically been Black's main
choice and it leads to a typical solid IQP position.} ({However, there is
something to be said about the alternative approach:} 12... Bxc3 $5 13. bxc3
Rc8 {[#] Black's idea is to prevent White from achieving the dominant c3-c4,
Bc1-b2 setup.} 14. Bg5 {This seems like the most principled move considering
that Black does not have the dark-squared bishop to break the pin anymore.} ({
Argentinian grandmaster Peralta, an expert in this variation, tried to achieve
