c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 b6 {[#] The third system that I
would like to recommend is a relatively rare, but strategically interesting
setup with b6 and Ba6. Instead of going for the isolated pawn type of position
by exchanging d- and c-pawns (as in Karpov and Larsen variation), Black keeps
some flexibility in the center. His main strategic goal is to trade off
light-squared bishops and, eventually, take control of light squares like e4
and c4. We will see some finer points of this system shortly, but overall it
has been scoring well in recent years for Black. I believe that it is a good
addition to the repertoire against 4.e3 because it provides some diversity in
terms of central pawn structures and middlegame ideas. Nimzo-Indian defense is
a very flexible opening and it is worth tapping into this flexibility when
possible. Naturally, White's most common continuation is} 7. O-O {but we also
need to take a look at two rare alternatives.} ({Firstly,} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Ne5
c5 (8... Ba6 {is also possible, leading to the same position via a different
move order:} 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 c5) 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Ba6 {[#] This is
the first typical pawn structure in this line and you may remember it from the
Ragozin database. After the inevitable trade of light-squared bishops, Black
usually pushes the pawn to c4, when the position becomes strategically
double-edged, with both sides trying to expand on opposite sides of the board.
From the examples below, we can see that Black is usually more successful than
White.} 11. Bxa6 (11. f3 Re8 {followed a similar script:} 12. Bb2 Bxd3 13. Qxd3
c4 14. Qc2 Nbd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Rae1 Qb7 17. a4 Re6 {1/2-1/2 (17) Peralta,F 
(2524)-Stefansson,H (2579) Turin 2006}) 11... Nxa6 12. a4 Re8 13. Qd3 Nb8 14.
Ba3 c4 15. Qf5 Qc7 16. f3 Nc6 17. Nxc6 Qxc6 18. Bc1 Re6 $15 19. Ra2 Rae8 20.
Qc2 Nd7 21. g4 Nf8 22. Qf2 Rg6 23. h3 f5 $1 $36 {0-1 (66) Romanov,E (2626)
-Cheparinov,I (2695) Mali Losinj 2017}) ({A slightly more respectable
continuation is:} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ba6 9. cxd5 {[#] and now Black has two
reasonable continuations:} Bxd3 ({He can also aim for type of position from 7.
Ne5 line with:} 9... exd5 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 {However, White can mess with his
plans by playing:} 11. Qd3 Qc8 12. c4 {and now a big cleanup in the center is
