Bonelli,E (2650) Baku 2016}) 11... c5 12. c4 Qe4 13. Qc3 {0-1 (41) Klinger,J 
(2495)-Lerner,K (2520) Polanica Zdroj 1985 and now} Rd8 $5 $146 14. Bb2 Nc6 $11
{gives Black full equality.}) 7... Ba6 {[#] The main line is 7...Bb7, leading
into a completely different type of position. This plan is more ambitious from
a strategic point of view because Black tries to trade an, arguably,
worse-placed bishop for the more active one. For that, he will incur a small
delay in development, while also having to worry about weakened c6-square and
backward c-pawn. On the other hand, there are several plusses to this trade.
Firstly, as I said, he solves the issue of his potentially most problematic
piece. Secondly, after the exchange, White will be the one with a passive
bishop, the dark-squared one. Thirdly, this exchange gives Black very good
play on the light squares and if he manages to get out of the first 15 or so
moves without any significant weaknesses, he usually has at least equal
chances in the long run. The position usually does not simplify too much,
there are very few forcing lines and opening theory of this variation is still
developing, so it can be a good opening choice if one is trying to play for a
win with Black. White usually releases the tension immediately with} 8. cxd5 ({
