{[%evp 0,12,34,25,30,8,14,4,10,-8,2,-54,-17,-75,11]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 {[#] The exchange on d5 leads to a considerably
different type of position compared to 5.a3 variation. Recapturing on d5 with
the queen is also a good option for Black, but I prefer 5...exd5 because we
get positions that are very similar to the 5.cxd5 exd5 variation of the
Ragozin defense. The difference compared to Ragozin is that white queen is
already on c2 and the knight is not on f3. For Black, this does not make a
significant difference at the start of the game because he still plans to
attack white center with ...c7-c5. However, it gives white some options
regarding development schemes - the knight can be developed to e2 instead of
f3, or he can castle queenside more quickly in some lines. Overall, this is a
sharp opening variation that requires a strong feeling for dynamics and
precise theoretical knowledge. Not surprisingly, White's most popular
continuation is} 6. Bg5 {pinning the knight, just like in the main line of the
Ragozin defense.} ({As I explained in the introduction, White usually prefers
to keep flexibility with knight's development, so} 6. Nf3 {is already not too
principled - White is essentially playing a strange-looking move 6.Qc2 in the
Ragozin. Black, naturally, attacks the d4-pawn with:} c5 7. Bg5 (7. dxc5 {
leads to a forced line:} d4 8. a3 Ba5 9. b4 dxc3 10. bxa5 Qxa5 11. e4 Nc6 12.
Rb1 Qxc5 $13 {with an interesting position.} 13. Rb5 Qe7 14. Bd3 Bg4 15. Be3
Bxf3 16. gxf3 O-O 17. Qxc3 Rfd8 18. O-O Rac8 $132 {1-0 (41) Danielian,E (2460)
-Muzychuk,A (2561) Lopota GEO 2014}) ({Another possibility is} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8.
bxc3 O-O {[#] leading into Ragozin territory.} 9. g3 $5 (9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 cxd4
11. Nxd4 Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. e3 Qd6 (13... Re8 $5 14. Bd3 c5 15. O-O g5 16.
Bg3 c4 17. Be2 Ne4 $132) 14. Bd3 Ng4 15. Bg3 Ne5 16. O-O Qf6 {1/2-1/2 (16)
Pachman,L-Matanovic,A Titovo Uzice 1966}) 9... Nc6 10. Bg2 cxd4 11. cxd4 Ne4
12. O-O Bf5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (36) Rybusia (2576)-OpenFormula (2589) playchess.com
INT 2007}) 7... h6 8. Bxf6 (8. Bh4 {transposes to 10.Nf3 in the main line
after:} g5 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. dxc5) 8... Qxf6 9. a3 {and here Black can use the
position of white queen to develop a piece:} Bf5 $5 ({Alternatively,} 9...
Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 {is covered in detail in the Ragozin database, Chapter 2.}) 10.
Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qb3 Bxc3+ 12. Qxc3 {and now the simplest way to equalize the game
