12. bxc3 Bxc3 13. Rc1 (13. Rb1 {was played in the game Grandelius,N (2632) -Yu,
Y (2736) Doha 2015 0-1 (32), when a possible improvement is:} Nd7 $5 $146 14.
e4 b6 $1 15. c6 Nf6 $132) 13... Bb4 14. e3 Nc6 15. Bd3 O-O 16. h4 g4 17. Bf4 {
[#] Black has a worse pawn structure, but the pin is still annoying for White.}
h5 ({A pawn sacrifice} 17... Re8 $5 18. Bxh6 Ne5 $132 {would up the ante.}) 18.
Bd6 Re8 19. Rd1 Nd4 20. Qb2 Bc3 21. Qb1 Nc6 22. Qc1 Bf6 23. Qb1 {1/2-1/2 (23)
O'Hare,C (2437)-Thorsteinsson,T (2438) ICCF email 2014}) 12. Nb3 {and now} Nxc5
$1 {initiates a forced sequence:} 13. Qxf5 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qxc3+ 15. Kd1 Nxb3
16. Qe5+ Qxe5 17. Bxe5 f6 $1 18. Bxf6 Rf8 19. axb3 Rxf6 20. f3 Nc6 $11 {
resulting in an equal endgame, in Martinovic,S (2563)-Hracek,Z (2594) Sibenik
2016 ½-½ (34)}) (10. O-O-O $5 Bxc3 11. f3 {[#] is a very interesting concept.
White sacrifices an exchange for control over dark squares. After:} Bd2+ 12.
Rxd2 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 {[#] I believe that it is best to continue} Be6 {preparing .
..Nb8-d7 and ...Ra8-c8 to attack the c5-pawn. The position is double-edged and
both sides have to be careful. White is threatening to squeeze Black with
moves like Bd6, Bb5 and Ne2-d4. However, the weak c-pawn is on the same file
as white king, which creates some tactical motives that Black can try to
exploit, as we will see.} 14. h4 {This is usually considered as a useful
inclusion for White as it disconnects black pawns in the kingside.} ({However,
White can obtain compensation even without this, by simply going:} 14. e3 Nd7
15. Bd6 (15. Qc3 $2 {is wrong on the account of:} O-O 16. Bd6 Rc8 $1 17. Bxf8
Qxf8 18. Kd2 Nxc5 $19 {0-1 (27) Deac,B (2289)-Raznikov,D (2479) Caleta 2014})
15... Rc8 16. Bb5 {[#] This happened in the game Lou,Y (2435) -Sethuraman,S 
(2527) Mashhad 2011 ½-½ (45) and now I suggest an improvement:} f6 $146 {
shutting down the long diagonal and clearing f7-square for the king.} (16... a6
{is strongly met by} 17. Qd4 $1) 17. b4 a6 18. Ba4 Kf7 19. Kb2 $44 {with a
complex position.}) 14... g4 {Of course, this is the standard reply to h2-h4
in such structures. Now, White has two ways to complete his kingside
development:} 15. Bd6 ({and more quietly, with:} 15. e3 Nd7 16. Bd6 Rc8 17. Bb5
{[#] Now, I believe that prophylactic move} Rg8 $5 $146 {is an important
novelty.} ({I am not so sure about Black's position after the previously played
} 17... a6 {1/2-1/2 (33) Rajlich,I (2411)-Sethuraman,S (2425) Budapest 2008
and now:} 18. Qd4 $5 Rg8 19. Ba4 b5 20. Bc2 Qa5 21. Ne2 gxf3 22. gxf3) 18. Ne2
({The point is that now} 18. Qd4 {can be met with a nice tactic:} Qb6 $3 {
a double attack!} 19. Bxd7+ Kxd7 20. Qa4+ Qc6 21. Qxc6+ Rxc6 22. Ne2 b6 $17)
18... a6 19. Bxd7+ (19. Ba4 b5 $17) 19... Qxd7 20. Nc3 gxf3 21. gxf3 b6 $1 {
[#] and this undermining move opens up the position at the right moment. It
remains a double-edged affair, as can be seen from variations below:} 22. Rd1 (
22. e4 bxc5 23. exd5 Qxd6 24. Ne4 Qe5 25. dxe6 Rd8 26. exf7+ Kxf7 27. Qxh6 Rd4
$13) 22... bxc5 23. Nxd5 Bxd5 24. Qxd5 Qe6 $13) 15... Nd7 16. e4 {[#] This is
a sharper option to which GM Erwin L'ami has found a good response:} Rc8 $1
$132 {Black obtains excellent counterplay along the c-file and White has to be
careful now.} 17. Qc3 $6 (17. Bb5 Qb6 $1 18. Qc3 Qxd6 19. Qxh8+ Qf8 20. Bxd7+
Bxd7 21. Qe5+ Qe7 $11) (17. Qd4 Qf6 18. e5 Qd8 $1 $13) (17. exd5 Nxc5 18. Bb5+
Bd7 19. Qe2+ Ne4+ $1 20. Kb1 Bxb5 21. Qxe4+ Kd7 $15) 17... Qf6 18. Qxf6 Nxf6
19. e5 Nd7 20. b4 a5 $1 21. a3 axb4 22. axb4 Ra8 $17 {0-1 (42) Navara,D (2638)
-L'Ami,E (2603) Wijk aan Zee 2009 CBM 129 [L'Ami,E]}) ({Finally, a rare move} 
10. Be5 $6 {should be checked.} O-O 11. e3 $6 (11. a3 {is somewhat better, but
still time-consuming.} Bxc3+ 12. Bxc3 Bf5 $36) 11... Nc6 12. Bd4 Qa5 13. Rc1
Re8 14. Be2 b6 15. a3 Nxd4 16. exd4 Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 bxc5 $19 {0-1 (19) Nicoara,
M (2237)-Leconte,M (2332) Gonfreville 2006}) 10... Qf6 $1 {This counterattack
is very strong.} ({A calmer alternative is} 10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Rxb8) 11. Bg3
{The critical reply.} ({In this case,} 11. Qa4+ $2 {does not work due to:} Bd7
12. Qxb4 Qxf2+ 13. Kd1 Qxf1+ 14. Kc2 Qxa1 15. Nxd5 Bf5 $1 {[#] and white king
proves to be a more vulnerable of the two.} 16. Qd4 Nxc5+ 17. e4 Bxe4+ 18. Kd2
Bxd5 19. Qxh8+ Kd7 20. Qd4 Ne4+ 21. Ke2 Rxb8 $19 {0-1 (59) Gunina,V (2528)
-Danielian,E (2488) Chengdu 2015}) (11. Nf3 {is a safe option for White, but
also not promising any advantage:} Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Rxb8 13. e3 O-O 14. Bd3 Nxc5
15. O-O Bd7 16. Nd4 Rbc8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (34) Dreev,A (2688)-Khairullin,I (2574)
Moscow 2009}) (11. e3 {can transpose into 11.Nf3 after} Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Rxb8 13.
Nf3) 11... Nxc3 12. a3 Bf5 13. Qd2 Ba5 {[#] After a forced tactical sequence,
we reached an unusual position. Black has a lot of tricks here, as we can see
from variations below:} 14. e3 (14. Nf3 {0-1 (30) Zymberi,A (2138)-Buckley,G 
(2383) London 2011 and now an important tactical resource is:} Nb1 $1 $146 {[#]
} 15. Qxa5 Qxb2 16. Qa4+ Bd7 17. Be5 Nc3 18. Qd1 $1 Nxd1 19. Bxb2 Nxb2 $11) (
14. b4 $2 Ne4 15. Qc1 Rc8 $1 $19 {This covert rook move basically decided the
outcome of the game Sokolov,I (2676)-Aronian,L (2756) Turin 2006 0-1 (19)})
14... O-O-O $1 {[#] The key move! Black mobilizes all his forces, increasing
the tension in the position. 15...d4 is a powerful threat.} 15. Bd6 $1 {
White needs to close down the d-file.} ({It is not difficult to go wrong in
such a tactically sharp position. One example is:} 15. b4 $2 d4 $1 16. Qb2 dxe3
17. fxe3 Rhe8 18. Rc1 Rxe3+ 19. Ne2 Rde8 $19 {0-1 (50) Shen,Y (2453)
-Kosintseva,T (2539) Sochi 2009}) 15... d4 16. Ne2 $1 {[#] The position has
reached its climax. White has covered his king and is threatening to win the
knight on c3. Fortunately, Black has a solution:} Bg4 $1 (16... dxe3 $2 17.
fxe3 Nxe2 18. Qxa5 $18 {would lose because of a mating threat on c7.}) 17. exd4
(17. bxc3 $2 dxc3 18. Qc2 Bf5 $19) 17... Ne4 $1 18. Qxa5 Qxf2+ 19. Kd1 Rd7 $44
{[#] and having defended against the checkmate, Black can focus on attacking
the exposed white king. In the following grandmaster game, a draw was reached
