{[%evp 0,13,34,30,27,14,14,18,11,-4,31,9,34,27,21,1]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. Qc2 b6 {[#] To add some diversity into our repertoire against 4.Qc2
Nimzo-Indian, I also analyze this rare system. Well, to be fair, it is not so
rare as it used to be, since its popularity has surged over the recent 4-5
years. Back in 2007, when I first started to study 4.Qc2 for White, I thought
that this variation is just bad because it surrenders the center to White.
However, recent practice has proven that this is definitely a playable system
for Black. It is often used to obtain non-standard positions and avoid
mainstream theory in 4...0-0 and 4...d5 variations. That being said, a
significant body of theoretical material has been developed in this line over
the last few years. In this and next chapter I will attempt to systemize this
material and offer the latest opening discoveries and trends in 4...b6
variation. In this chapter, we will take a look at the critical reply:} 5. e4 {
White was allowed to establish a strong pawn center, so Black's concept is
somewhat hypermodernistic - he undermines it with:} c5 {[#] With great power
comes great responsibility. Yes, White has an impressive center, but he also
needs to make sure to protect it. The most principled way to do that is} 6. d5
{Once again, as a 4.Qc2 player myself, I can not shake off the feeling that
White should have an edge if he plays this way. Yet, practice has shown that
this is far from an easy task and Black's score in this line has been
encouraging, especially playing against lower-rated opposition.} (6. e5 {
is an ambitious reply, but it is going along Black's plot to provoke central
expansion and attack weaknesses that are left behind. It is well-known that
pawns do not move backwards!} cxd4 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ng8 {[#] Black's
development looks ridiculous at the first sight, but White is not any better
developed himself. Over the next several moves, Black follows a simple
development scheme: ...Bb7, ...Nc6, ...Nge7. After that he can attack c4- and
d4-pawns with ...Nc6-a5, ...Ra8-c8 and ...Ne7-f5, ...Qd8-h4, respectively.} 9.
cxd4 ({The alternative is} 9. Qe4 Nc6 10. cxd4 ({White could try to play the
Nimzo-version of poisoned pawn variation of the Winawer French with:} 10. Qg4
Nge7 11. Qxg7 Rg8 12. Qxh7 Qc7 {[#] This is indeed very similar to the
afore-mentioned variation of the French defense. However, it is obviously a
better version for Black.} 13. Bf4 dxc3 14. Nf3 Bb7 15. Rc1 O-O-O $15) 10...
Bb7 11. Qg4 ({White can go 'all-in' with his central expansion, but} 11. d5 {
looks too good to be true. The pawns become an easy pray after:} Nce7 12. Qg4
Ng6 13. Nf3 exd5 14. Bb2 ({Better was} 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Bd3 $44) 14... Nh6 $1
15. Qd4 Nf5 16. Qg4 Nfh4 17. O-O-O Rc8 18. Kb1 h5 19. Qd4 Nf5 20. Qd3 Nge7 21.
Qb3 Rc5 22. cxd5 Bxd5 $17 {0-1 (39) Abdyjapar,A (2372)-Meskovs,N (2535) Batumi
GEO 2018}) (11. Nf3 {probably just transposes to 11.Qg4 after} Nge7 12. Qg4 Nf5
) 11... Nge7 12. Nf3 Nf5 13. Bd3 (13. d5 $5 {has not been played before, but
deserves attention. After:} h5 (13... Nce7 14. Bg5) 14. Qf4 Nce7 15. Bd3 {
