{[%evp 0,9,28,21,15,15,15,15,20,20,41,9]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3
{[#] Statistically, this is White's third most popular move against the
Nimzo-Indian. It is not a very pretentious move because pretty much any of the
typical black answers are okay for him. The advantage of such an approach for
White is that he remains flexible by playing the most natural move, and waits
for Black to show his cards first. Of course, it is immediately obvious that
we can transpose into the Ragozin defense with 4...d5 and we can end the story
there. However, what if you do not want to play the Ragozin for one reason or
another? Maybe your opponent sees in database that you like to play the
Ragozin against 3.Nf3, so he tries to drag you into it from this move order?
As I said before, it is good to have options and thus I would like to suggest
an alternative:} b6 {This move is also quite flexible and can lead to
different types of Nimzo-indian positions. It is also consistent with 'sharp
repertoire' recommendations against 4.e3 and 4.Qc2 variations. We can see this
from possible transpositions below. White has many ways to answer queen's
fianchetto. The most common continuation is} 5. Bg5 (5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 d5 {
transposes into Chapter 8,}) ({while} 5. Qc2 Bb7 {transposes into Chapter 14.})
({Let us now take a look at some independent alternatives. Second by
popularity is:} 5. Qb3 {This forces the answer} c5 {[#] This puts pressure on
white center, which can be strengthened with ...Nb8-c6, so Black has nothing
to complain about.} 6. Bg5 {Once again, pinning the knight is the most common
continuation.} ({White can also release central tension with:} 6. dxc5 Bxc5 {
[#] This has some similarities with 4.Qc2 c5 variation (that is not covered in
this database). The downside for White is that his queen is not placed to well
on b3 as it is on c2. Still, Black needs to know what he is doing here.} 7. Bf4
({In case of} 7. Bg5 Bb7 8. e3 {Karpov has showed the way for Black:} Be7 9.
Rd1 O-O 10. Be2 Na6 $1 {using the position of white queen to win a tempo} 11.
O-O Nc5 12. Qc2 Nce4 $11 {[#]} 13. Bxf6 (13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11) 13...
Nxf6 14. e4 d6 15. Rd2 Qc7 {and Black is fine.} 16. Rfd1 a6 $11 17. Nd4 Rfd8
18. Qd3 Bf8 19. Qh3 e5 20. Nf5 Nxe4 21. Nxe4 Bxe4 22. Ne3 b5 23. cxb5 axb5 24.
Bxb5 Rxa2 $15 {1/2-1/2 (72) Piket,J (2615)-Karpov,A (2725) Roquebrune 1992})
7... Bb7 8. e3 O-O 9. Rd1 {[#] This was played in the game Stocek,J (2561)
-Brunello,S (2391) Trieste 2006 1-0 (41). I believe that Black should play the
