{[%evp 0,12,28,18,23,15,21,20,28,-38,3,8,11,12,36]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. f3 c5 {[#] This is obviously a sharper approach to 4.f3 Nimzo-indian.
Black allows White to build up his solid Saemisch pawn chain (g2-f3-e4-d5),
but banks on his lead in development. Strategically, this can be a risky
approach because, in case something goes wrong, Black does not have a safety
net and can easily end up with an inferior pawn structure and lack of space.
His advantage lies in the tactical potential of his better-developed pieces,
which often helps him undermine and, sometimes, destroy white strong pawn
chain in the center. Needless to say, precise knowledge of variations is of
the essence in this variation. But if one manages to combine knowledge of
important theoretical lines with tactical awareness, he can reap great rewards
because this variation is equally demanding for White. The main reply is:} 5.
d5 ({while} 5. a3 {transposes into the next chapter after:} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 7.
e4 Nc6 {- Nimzo-Indian with 4.a3}) 5... O-O 6. e4 ({There is no point in
postponing e2-e4, as we can see from the game below:} 6. Bg5 Re8 7. e4 $4 exd5
8. cxd5 Nxe4 $1 {A typical tactical shot in these positions.} 9. Bxd8 Nxc3+ 10.
Kf2 Nxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Rxd8 $19 {0-1 (13) Jukic,Z (2254)-Kuljasevic,D (2431)
Zagreb 2005}) {Among several alternatives, I would like to recommend the
sharpest one} 6... b5 $5 {[#] This Benko-like move allows White to expand his
central control with 7.e5 Ne8 8.f4, but things are far from simple there, as
we will see. The alternatives are} (6... d6) ({and} 6... Re8 {which usually
leads to a Benoni type of structure. While this is a perfectly viable approach,
it usually allows White to keep his center and gives rise to maneuvering play
to a certain degree. However, 6...b5 really challenges white pawn center,
whether he keeps the pawn on e4 or moves it forward.}) {White has a host of
options at this point. The most principled one is, obviously:} 7. e5 ({The
next important variation is} 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 {and now Black has two good
continuations:} Re8 {[#] This move prevents 9.e5, while also setting up the ...
Nxe4 trap.} ({and} 8... d6 $5 {which, I believe, was analyzed in a book on
Nimzo-Indian by GM Michael Roiz. The critical line might be} 9. Bd3 exd5 10.
cxd5 c4 11. Bc2 {with sharp play on both flanks.}) {White usually reacts in
the center with either} 9. dxe6 ({or} 9. d6 {although this gives Black a
convenient way to develop his knight:} bxc4 10. Bxc4 Nc6 11. f4 (11. Nh3 Ne5
12. Be2 Ng6 $13) {and now the cool} 11... Bb7 $1 {offers Black a plenty of
counterplay, as can be seen in variations below:} 12. Nf3 (12. e5 {is met by}
Qa5 $1 13. Nge2 Ng4 14. Qd3 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Nd4 $1 16. O-O $1 Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2
Qxc3 $132) 12... Na5 13. Bd3 $6 (13. Ne5 {was better.} Nxc4 14. Nxc4 Bxe4 15.
O-O $44) 13... c4 $1 14. Bc2 Qb6 $36 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. e5 Qe3+ 17. Qe2 Qxf4 18.
O-O f5 19. Rad1 Bc5+ 20. Kh1 Qe3 $17 {0-1 Wallace,J (2388)-Hawkins,J (2550)/
England 2015/EXT 2016 (40)}) 9... Rxe6 {[#] Black still threatens ...Nxe4, so
White should continue:} 10. Nge2 (10. Bd3 $2 {1-0 Simantsev,M (2549)
-Stojanovski,D (2427)/Kraljevo 2011/CBM 144 Extra (45) runs into} Nxe4 $1 11.
Bxd8 Nxc3+ 12. Kf2 Nxd1+ 13. Rxd1 bxc4 14. Bxc4 Re8 $17) ({as well as} 10. Nh3
$6 Nxe4 $1 11. Bxd8 Nxc3+ 12. Kf2 Nxd1+ 13. Rxd1 bxc4 14. a3 (14. Bxc4 Re8 15.
Bd5 Nc6 16. Bc7 Ba6 $15) 14... Nc6 15. axb4 Nxd8 16. Bxc4 Rb6 $15) ({while} 10.
cxb5 {gives Black a free hand in the center after} d5 $36) {This was played in
the game Volkov,S (2554)-Sakaev,K (2627) New Delhi/Teheran 2000 0-1 (43),
which can be significantly improved with} 10... Bb7 $1 $146 {[#] Black
increases his control over the key d5-square. He may also still be threatening
to sacrifice a piece on e4 in certain lines. White has many possibilities,
which are analyzed below, and it seems like it is not easy for him to complete
