1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {[#] While it used to be a
dangerous weapon in the early days of Nimzo-Indian defense, Saemisch variation
is not too popular these days because Black has found proper methods to
contain White's ambitious setup. The cornerstone of black strategy, as I
explained in the introduction, is the blockade of c4-pawn with} c5 {Now, White
has two basic setups. A more popular one is} 6. e3 {supporting d4-pawn and
planning to expand in the center only once he has completed his kingside
development.} ({The second one is:} 6. f3 {preparing to establish pawn center
straight away. You may notice that 6...d5 now would transpose directly into
