in this chapter:} d6 7. e4 ({In case of} 7. d5 O-O 8. e4 {[#] White lags in
development and Black can use this time to attack his center with:} Nh5 $1 9.
Ne2 f5 $36 10. Qc2 exd5 11. cxd5 Nd7 12. c4 fxe4 13. Qxe4 Ne5 $19 {0-1 (54)
Mainka,W-Hilmer,F (2220) Bad Zwesten 2001}) ({One additional idea is:} 7. Nh3
O-O 8. Nf2 {when Black can continue with business as usual:} Nc6 9. e4 b6 10.
Bg5 {and now the pin can be broken in the following way:} h6 11. Bh4 e5 12. d5
Na5 13. Bd3 g5 14. Bg3 Nh5 $132) 7... Nc6 {[#] A downside of this setup is
that d4-pawn has one defender less, so White can not develop with 8.Bd3 as in
the main line. Thus, the most common continuation is} 8. Be3 {protecting the
pawn and attacking the one on c5.} ({Another viable setup is} 8. Ne2 b6 9. Bg5
(9. Ng3 O-O 10. d5 {is less principled because Black gets excellent
