{[%evp 0,14,19,31,14,-14,-11,-9,-3,-7,-7,4,-11,-30,-9,-8,-1]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 {The Nimzo-Catalan hybrid has become fairly popular lately
thanks to the development of some new ideas for White. I will remain faithful
to .. .d7-d5 Nimzo/Ragozin setup against 4.g3, as well. Moreover, the position
after 4...d5 5.Nf3 was referenced in the Ragozin database, so you may refer to
this chapter if you are wondering what to play if someone goes 5.g3 against
the Ragozin.} d5 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nf3 {This is the main continuation, sacrificing
the c4-pawn, although White can also aim for various Carlsbad setups by
exchanging on d5.} ({The first such option is:} 6. a3 Be7 ({The alternative is
} 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Qa4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. f3 $1 $13 {with a complex
middlegame.}) 7. cxd5 (7. Qd3 {is a reasonable way to defend the c4-pawn, but
it neglects development. Black can take advantage of that with a typical motif:
} c5 8. dxc5 Nbd7 $1 {[#] We have seen this idea in many Nimzo positions so
far. Here, it makes even more sense because of the queen's exposed position 
(both Nxc5 and Ne5 are threatening).} 9. cxd5 Nxc5 10. Qd1 {and now both
captures deserve attention:} exd5 ({as well as:} 10... Nxd5 $5 11. Nxd5 exd5 {
As in some lines of QGD, the point of taking on d5 with the knight is to
vacate f6-square for the bishop.} 12. Be3 Ne6 13. Nf3 ({Black's activity gives
him full compensation in case of:} 13. Qxd5 Bf6 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Rb1 Nd4 $44)
13... Bf6 14. Nd4 Re8 $1 {and now} 15. O-O {lead to mass-simplifications after:
} Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Rxe2 18. Rac1 Re7 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Bxd5 Bh3 $11
{1/2-1/2 (24) El Debs,F (2531)-Wojtaszek,R (2745) Tbilisi 2017}) 11. Nf3 ({
White's lag in development is too big to go into:} 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 (12.
