} Nh5 $1 $146 15. Bd2 (15. Be3 g6 $17) 15... Nb3 16. g4 d4 $1 17. gxh5 dxc3 18.
Bxc3 Qc8 $15) 11... b5 12. Rad1 c6 $1 {[#] This is perhaps the only subtle
detail that needs to be remembered in this line: when the bishop is on f4,
Black should play 12...c6, and when it is on e3, he should play 12...Bb7.} ({
In case of} 12... Bb7 {White's} 13. d5 {gains in strength as the bishop is
placed better on f4 than e3 in such a position (compare to 10.Be3)}) 13. h4 {
Postny was probably not too happy about 13.d5, so he decided for kingside
expansion instead.} ({Now,} 13. d5 {, which works fine in a similar position
in 10.Be3 line, is not so strong because after the forced sequence:} cxd5 14.
exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Rxd5 {Black plays} Qb6 $1 {[#] (this
square is not available with bishop on e3) and gets a good position:} 18. Rxg5
Bb7 19. Qc3 f6 $15) {However, Black played excellently from this point on,
neutralizing all potential threats and achieving a clearly better position:}
13... h6 14. Ne5 Bb7 15. g4 Nb3 16. Be3 Nd7 $1 $15 17. g5 hxg5 18. Nxd7 Qxd7
19. hxg5 {[#]} c5 $1 $17 {1/2-1/2 (25) Postny,E (2653)-Markidis,K (2291)
Rethymno 2012}) 10... a6 11. Qc2 ({Once again, I find} 11. Qe2 {to be a
slightly inferior queen placement. After:} b5 12. Rad1 Bb7 13. Ne5 Qe8 $1 {
[#] is a good idea for Black, preparing Rad8, c5, etc. It works because there
is a queen on e2 and not the rook on e1. After} 14. g4 ({or} 14. Bg5 Rd8 15.
Ng4 $2 Nxg4 16. Qxg4 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Nb3 $17 {0-1 Kanter,E (2410)-Beliavsky,A 
(2643)/Yerevan 2014/CBM 160 (39)}) 14... Rd8 15. f4 Nb3 16. g5 Nd7 $15 {
Black's position is for preference. For example:} 17. h4 f6 $1 18. Nxc4 c5 $1
$17) 11... b5 12. Rad1 {[#] and now the game Delorme,A (2494)-Campos Moreno,J 
(2458) Chambery 2014 1-0 (32) can be improved with:} Bb7 $5 $146 ({This time
around,} 12... c6 {is inferior, because after} 13. d5 $1 exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15.
Nxd5 cxd5 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Rxd5 $44 {there is no 17...Qb6, and White gets a
better version of this idea. Devil is in the detail!}) 13. d5 ({As usual, slow
plans like} 13. Ne5 {give Black enough time to centralize his forces:} Nb3 14.
f4 Qe8 15. Rfe1 c5 16. d5 Rd8 $15) 13... Qe8 $1 {[#] Black does not want to
open up the position (yet). This move would not be available to Black in a
similar position with bishop on f4 as c7-pawn would be hanging. Now we get an
interesting position with many possibilities for both sides:} ({Instead,} 13...
exd5 14. exd5 Bd6 15. Nd4 $44 {would give White a lot of active options.}) 14.
Bf4 (14. Bh3 Nb3 $1 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. Bxe6+ Kh8 $15) (14. Nd4 $6 Ng4) 14... Bd8
$1 15. Rfe1 (15. Nd2 Nd7 $1 16. Rfe1 e5 17. Be3 Be7 $15) 15... Nb3 $13) 8...
Nd5 $1 {This is the best answer. All other moves have some tactical drawback.}
(8... Bd7 9. Bg5 $1 Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nxd4 11. Qxc4 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 $36) (8... Rb8
9. Qb5 $1 $14) (8... a6 9. Ne5 $1 $36) (8... a5 9. a3 $14) 9. Qc2 {Having
provoked 8...Nd5 that shields the d4-pawn from queen's attack, White retreats
his queen and prepares central expansion with e2-e4, Rd1, Be3, etc., just like
in variation 8.a3 Be7 9.e4.} Be7 {In the view of this plan, it makes sense to
vacate b4-square for one of the knights (to reach d3 via b4).} 10. Rd1 {
[#] This is a major crossroad for Black. He has several playable continuations
and it is not easy to pick the 'best' one among them. At the end, I decided
for the simplest one:} Rb8 {with which I have also had some personal
experience.} ({Alternatives are} 10... Ncb4 11. Qd2 c5) ({and} 10... b6 11. e4
Ndb4 12. Qe2 Ba6) 11. e4 ({Preventing the knight jump to b4 with} 11. a3 {
takes time and weakens b3-square, so Black can simply continue:} Na5 12. e4
Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Nb3 14. Rb1 b5 $15 {0-1 (31) Ristic,N (2420)-Gabriel,C (2495)
Passau 1996}) 11... Ncb4 {[#]} ({I believe that the other knight jump:} 11...
Ndb4 {is slightly inferior due to:} 12. Qe2 Nd3 13. Be3 b5 14. b3 Ba6 15. d5 $1
Bf6 16. dxc6 Bxc3 17. Rab1 $14 {1/2-1/2 (64) Spasov,S (2315)-Bueno,T (2161)
ICCF email 2009}) {White has three queen moves at this point. The most
interesting one is probably:} 12. Qd2 {which was played in De Firmian,N (2540)
-Kudrin,S (2485) Estes Park 1985 1-0 (57)} ({The most popular one, though, is:
} 12. Qb1 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd3 {with the point that White finally retrieves the
pawn with} 14. Qb5 {However, I believe that the position after:} Nxc1 15. Raxc1
c5 $11 {[#] is completely fine for Black. White has a stronger presence in the
center, but Black is extremely solid, and his bishop pair should not be
underestimated in the long run.} 16. Qxc4 ({The following game is a case in
point:} 16. Ne5 Qc7 17. f4 Rd8 18. Kh1 f6 19. Nf3 cxd4 20. cxd4 Bd7 21. Qxc4
Qxc4 22. Rxc4 Rbc8 $15 {0-1 (49) Teran Alvarez, I (2377)-Santos Ruiz,M (2517)
Linares ESP 2018}) 16... b5 17. Qe2 Qb6 18. Ne5 {1/2-1/2 (34) Onischuk,A (2667)
-Naroditsky,D (2646) Saint Louis 2017} Qc7 $5 $146 19. Ng4 Bd7 20. Ne3 Rfc8
$132) (12. Qe2 {is a move that I have faced myself:} Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd3 14. Ne5
{Trading the strong knight, but corrupting his pawn structure.} (14. a4 $1 {
is the right idea, planning to win the c-pawn via a2!} Bd7 15. Qa2 c5 16. Qxc4
Nxc1 17. Raxc1 Qa5 $132 {and this is similar to 12.Qb1.}) 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 {
½-½ (45) Bukal,V (2416)-Kuljasevic,D (2555) Sibenik 2012} Bd7 16. Qxc4 c5 $15
) {Here, I suggest we continue:} 12... Nxc3 $5 $146 13. Qxc3 {This is the
difference compared to 12.Qb1 and 12.Qe2. Now we get a different pawn
structure. It is logical for both sides to continue:} b5 14. b3 Ba6 {[#] Such
positions are quite common in the closed Catalan. Their assessment often
depends on tactical details. In this particular case, I have made some
analysis (below) and concluded that Black is fine:} 15. Ne1 (15. bxc4 bxc4 16.
Ne5 c5 $1 17. Bf4 Bf6 18. dxc5 Qc8 $11) 15... Nc6 16. Be3 Qd6 $1 17. bxc4 (17.
Bf1 e5 $1 18. dxe5 (18. d5 Nd4 19. bxc4 c5 $11) 18... Qxe5 19. Qxe5 Nxe5 20.
Bxa7 Ra8 $11) 17... bxc4 18. Nc2 Nb4 $11 *

