{[%evp 0,16,25,19,23,15,4,4,28,-10,-22,-26,-17,-23,-57,-16,-27,0,10]} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {[#] This used to be Boris Spassky's favorite
weapon against the Nimzo-Indian defense. After that, it was picked up by
world-class grandmasters like Jan Timman and Artur Jussupow. It even had a
resurgence in grandmaster arena around the year 2010. However, history is one
thing and present another. The current state of theory in this line is very
encouraging for Black and it is not surprising that very few strong players
have used this opening with White in recent 2-3 years. The problem for White
is that he can hardly justify the pawn sacrifice in the main line of this
variation. It may be necessary to look for new ideas in some less explored
branches of this system to revive it.} c5 5. d5 d6 6. e3 ({White can also set
up the Neo-Saemisch structure with} 6. f3 O-O 7. e4 {Now, an informative
intermediate move} h6 {does not hurt. White has two options:} 8. Bh4 ({or} 8.
Bd2 {when Black has a strong maneuver that we have seen in Chapter 18:} exd5 9.
cxd5 Nh5 $1 10. Nge2 f5 $36 {0-1 (38) Parker,J (2539)-Lautier,J (2648)
Mondariz 2000}) 8... Re8 $1 {This move disrupts White's development, just like
in some lines from Chapter 17. White is forced to develop awkwardly with:} 9.
Nge2 exd5 10. cxd5 Nbd7 11. Qc2 Ne5 {This is a standard maneuver in these
structures.} 12. a3 Ba5 13. Nc1 {[#] when Black wins the bishop pair:} Ng6 14.
Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Bb5 Re7 16. O-O a6 17. Be2 b5 $17 {with a clear positional
advantage in Mamedyarov,S (2799)-Korobov,A (2652) Huaian 2017 0-1 (27)}) 6...
exd5 $1 {This concrete approach is the best.} ({The alternative is} 6... Bxc3+
7. bxc3 e5 {with a completely different type of position, which was more
popular in the pre-computer era.}) 7. cxd5 Nbd7 {Black prepares 8...Qa5 in the
spirit of Cambridge-Springs variation. White's problem is that he has to give
up the central pawn to achieve the ideal setup with Bd3, Nge2.} 8. Bd3 ({
The main alternative is} 8. Bb5 {when I suggest the following reply:} h6 9. Bh4
Bxc3+ $5 10. bxc3 Qa5 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. Ne2 O-O $1 {[#] This position arose
practically by force. Black's last move is strong because taking the d6-pawn
is risky for White.} 13. Be7 ({It is more prudent to complete development:} 13.
O-O $5 Re8 {although that does not trouble Black at all, either.} 14. Qc2 (14.
Bg3 Qa6 $132) 14... b5 15. Bg3 Nf6 16. Bxd6 Qb6 17. Bg3 Nxd5 $11) 13... Re8 14.
Bxd6 {All of this was seen in Korobov,A (2720)-Kramnik,V (2784)/Tromsoe 2013/
CBM 156 (58) ½-½ and now an important improvement is:} Nf6 $1 $146 15. O-O
Bg4 16. f3 Rad8 $1 $15) 8... Qa5 9. Nge2 Nxd5 {Black wins the pawn, but White
gets some compensation after:} 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 {Only like this.} (11.
Nxc3 $4 {allows the kindergarten Cambridge-Springs trick:} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c4 $19
) 11... c4 $1 {[#] This is a very important move in Black's setup because it
helps him include his queen in the game via the fifth rank, while also
preventing White from going c3-c4 himself, which would most definitely give
him compensation for a pawn, if not more.} 12. Bc2 {This is the best bishop
move.} (12. Bxc4 $4 {loses a piece to} N5b6 $19) ({While other moves allow
exchanges that make Black's life easier:} 12. Bf5 O-O 13. e4 Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Qxc3
15. Rc1 Qe5 16. Rxc4 Nb6 $15 {0-1 Jacob,V (2280)-Luther,T (2533)/Austria 2005/
EXT 2005 (44)}) ({and:} 12. Be4 N5f6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Bf3 d5 15. Qd4 O-O 16.
g4 Be6 17. Rfb1 b6 $15 {1-0 (59) Ovetchkin,R (2501)-Lysyj,I (2632) St
Petersburg 2012}) 12... O-O {[#] A critical moment for White. This might have
been considered as a promising position for White some time ago, but in recent
years, strong engines have proven that most of White's active ideas are either
easily neutralized or outright refuted.} 13. Bh4 {It is best to remove the
bishop from there to avoid discovered attack after ...Nxc3.} ({One of such
ideas is:} 13. Ng3 Nxc3 14. Qh5 {when} f5 $1 {basically puts 13.Ng3 line out
of business.} 15. Be7 ({Third consecutive pawn sacrifice is too much:} 15. e4
Nxe4 16. Rad1 Ndf6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 $19 {0-1 Georgiev,V (2566)-Leko,P (2737)/
Istanbul 2012/CBM 151 (28)}) 15... Rf7 $1 {This is an important improvement
over one of Wojtaszek's games.} 16. Nxf5 {White threatens to win the queen and
probably a few other things,} (16. Bxd6 Nf6 17. Qh4 Be6 $17) {but it is
refuted by:} 16... Ne5 $1 {[#] Now, Black is the one who will threaten a
discovered attack along the fifth rank!} 17. Bxd6 (17. Nxg7 Nf3+ 18. Kh1 Qxh5
19. Nxh5 Rxe7 20. gxf3 b5 $17) 17... Bxf5 18. Bxf5 {0-1 (51) Rain,R (2241)
-Ronat,O (2317) ICCF email 2014} Nf3+ $5 19. Qxf3 Qxf5 20. Qxf5 Ne2+ $1 21. Kh1
Rxf5 $19 {and black queenside pawns are running much faster than those on the
other side of the board.}) (13. Qd4 {is a reasonable option, since White keeps
some compensation for the pawn after:} Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Qxg5 15. Qxc4 Nf6 16. Ne4
Nxe4 17. Qxe4 g6 18. Bb3 $44 {[#] However, only Black can play for the win
here.} Rb8 19. Qd4 b6 20. Qxd6 Bb7 21. Qg3 Qxg3 22. hxg3 $15 {and the ensuing
endgame was unpleasant for White in the game Dekker,A (2230)-Van der Werf,M 
(2370) Dieren 1991 0-1 (50) because Black virtually has an extra pawn.}) ({
Finally, in case of} 13. Nd4 Nxc3 14. Qh5 {as in Bareev,E (2605)-Dautov,R 
(2555) Moscow 1990 ½-½ (43), Black should answer the same way as in 13.Ng3
line:} f5 $1 $146 {and after} 15. Be7 Nf6 $1 {[#] solidifies his position on
the kingside, and White is down a full pawn for no compensation.} 16. Qh4 Rf7
17. Bxd6 Nce4 $17) 13... Nxc3 14. Nxc3 ({White achieves little with:} 14. Bxh7+
Kxh7 15. Qc2+ Kg8 16. Nxc3 Ne5 $17 {and Black centralizes his knight with a
strong effect.} 17. e4 ({White's problem is that, even if he takes the pawn:} 
17. Be7 Re8 18. Bxd6 {Black achieves complete positional domination with} Nd3
$17) 17... Re8 18. Rab1 {[#] Now, Black found an elegant tactical idea to
increase his advantage:} Nf3+ $3 19. gxf3 Qh5 20. Bg3 Qxf3 21. Nd5 (21. Qe2
Qxc3 $17) 21... Bh3 22. Ne3 Rxe4 $40 {with a winning attack for Black in Xiong,
J (2550)-Grover, S (2498)/Dallas 2015/CBM 169 Extra (46) 0-1}) 14... Qxc3 15.
Rc1 {[#]} Qe5 {This is the most human move.} (15... Qa3 $5 {is preference of
correspondence players. One such example is:} 16. Be4 Re8 17. Rxc4 Nb6 18. Rd4
d5 19. Bb1 Bd7 20. Rf4 Be6 21. Qc2 f5 22. Qd1 Rf8 23. Qh5 g6 24. Qh6 Rf7 25.
Bg3 Qf8 26. Qxf8+ Raxf8 $15 {0-1 (90) Avotins,M (2458)-Puzone,M (2403) ICCF
email 2012}) 16. Bg3 (16. f4 $6 {is 'all-in' approach, but it does not work
against solid defense, as in this game:} Qc5 $1 17. Kh1 Re8 18. e4 b5 19. Bf2
Qc7 (19... Qc6 $1 20. Bd4 Nc5 $19) 20. Bd4 Bb7 21. Qg4 f6 $17 {0-1 Hoi,C (2386)
-Svane,R (2549)/ Helsingor 2016/CBM 173 Extra (40)}) 16... Qe6 {[#] White can
win one pawn immediately and hope to utilize his bishop pair and more active
pieces to retrieve the second one. However, it feels like he is the one who
has to prove more in this variation, while Black's choices are not too
difficult and he runs very few risks, despite a certain lag in development.}
17. Qxd6 ({The another option is:} 17. Bxd6 Re8 $15 18. e4 Ne5 19. f4 Nd3 20.
Bxd3 cxd3 21. Qxd3 Qxe4 22. Rce1 Qxe1 23. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 24. Kf2 Re8 25. f5 Rd8 $17
{with good winning chances for Black in Yilmaz,M (2543)-Palac,M (2599)/
Istanbul 2012/CBM 151 ½-½ (35)}) 17... Qxd6 18. Bxd6 $44 {[#] White will
have some compensation in the endgame, but not more than that.} Re8 19. Rfd1 ({
In case of} 19. Bd1 $5 Re6 20. Bf4 Ne5 21. Bxe5 Rxe5 22. Rxc4 {we get an
endgame that is very similar to the game from the 13.Qd4 line above. It is
drawish, but Black's pawn majority still gives him chances to play for more.})
19... Nb6 (19... Nf6 $5 {is also an option, allowing b-pawn to move.}) 20. a4 {
This lead to a drawish, but slightly unpleasant endgame for White.} (20. Bc5 $5
{was better, just leading to a draw. For instance:} Be6 21. Be4 Rac8 22. Bd6 c3
23. Bxb7 c2 24. Rd4 Rc4 25. Be4 Rec8 26. Bd3 Rxd4 27. exd4 Bxa2 28. Bxc2 $11)
20... Bd7 21. a5 Na4 22. Bb4 Bb5 23. Rd5 a6 $15 {0-1 (57) Martinovic,S (2538)
-Stevic,H (2618) Plitvicka Jezera 2013} *

