{[%evp 0,12,20,20,20,0,-13,-11,4,20,25,26,27,13,24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. Bd2 {[#] This modest-looking system has gained popularity in recent
years. White prepares to take back with the bishop on c3 in case Black decides
to make the exchange. He usually develops simply with e3, Nf3, Bd3, etc., so
there is a lot of overlap with positions from Chapters 1-8. In fact, another
common move order to get the position from the main line in this file is: 4.e3
0-0 5.Nf3 d5 6.Bd2.} O-O 5. e3 ({Another typical middlegame position for this
line arises after:} 5. a3 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Ne4 {(this move should be played before
White gets time to retreat the bishop to b2)} 7. Qc2 Nxc3 8. Qxc3 b6 9. Nf3 Bb7
10. e3 d6 11. Be2 Nd7 12. O-O c5 13. Rfd1 Qe7 $11 {[#] and Black is completely
fine.} 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nd2 Rac8 16. Rac1 Rc7 17. b4 Nd7 18. Qd4 Rfc8 19. Nb3
Qg5 20. g3 Qg6 21. Qf4 e5 $13 {0-1 (53) Mirzoev,A (2617)-Granda Zuniga,J (2640)
Pamplona 2009}) (5. Nf3 d5 6. e3 {is another move order to reach the main line.
}) 5... d5 6. Nf3 ({Another plan is:} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bd3 Re8 8. Nge2 {
transposing into Chapter 2.}) ({In case of} 6. a3 {I suggest} Be7 {when Black
intends to play a QGD in which white bishop is not placed so well on d2, as it
would be on f4, g5, or even b2.} 7. Nf3 b6 {The plan is to fianchetto the
bishop and play the middlegame with hanging pawns.} 8. Rc1 (8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O
c5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Qb1 Nbd7 12. Rd1 Re8 $11 13. b4 $6 c4 14. Bc2 Bd6 15. Be1
a6 $15 {0-1 (55) Bykhovsky,A (2411)-Movsesian,S (2655) Teplice 2015}) 8... Bb7
9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 c5 $11 11. dxc5 bxc5 {[#] In this typical middlegame pawn
structure, the bishop is misplaced on d2.} 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Na4 Ne4 14. Bc3
Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Rc8 $15 {0-1 (52) Schaufelberger,H (2268)-Tukmakov,V (2595)
Basel 2001}) 6... b6 {[#] With the bishop on d2, this is the preferred setup
because it gives Black more flexibility than 6...c5.} (6... c5 {is considered
as the main reply against 6.Bd3 system in Rubinstein variation; however, is
not too attractive here since White gets a risk-free position with a minimum
plus after:} 7. a3 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ne4 9. Rc1 Nxc3 10. Rxc3 {and if Black clears
up the center with:} cxd4 11. Nxd4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 {[#] White has a slight
positional pressure in the arising type of position.} Bd7 13. O-O Nc6 14. Nf3
Qe7 15. Qc2 $14 {as in the game Rakhmanov,A (2627)-Goganov,A (2576) Ankara
2018 1-0 (47)}) {White's most principled response to 6...b6 is} 7. cxd5 {
immediately defining central pawn structure.} ({Below are some rare
alternatives:} 7. Rc1 Bb7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Be2 ({It is more usual to develop
the bishop to b1-h7 diagonal} 9. Bd3 {transposing into 7.cxd5.}) 9... a6 ({
The other reasonable setup is} 9... Be7 $5 10. Ne5 c5 11. O-O Nc6) 10. O-O Bd6
11. Ne5 c5 12. Be1 {This typical bishop maneuver was played in Matlakov,M 
(2694)-Anton Guijarro,D (2650) Tallinn 2016 1-0 (41) and now} Nc6 $146 {
is a possible improvement, leading to a similar position to the main line,
only with the bishop on e2 instead of d3. Possible variations are:} 13. Ng4 (
13. f4 cxd4 14. Nxc6 (14. exd4 $2 Nxd4 $17) 14... Bxc6 15. exd4 $11) (13. Nxc6
Bxc6 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Bf3 Qc7 16. g3 Rad8 $13) 13... cxd4 14. exd4 Nxg4 15.
Bxg4 Re8 $11) (7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O {This is an attempt to take advantage of the
fact that White has not taken on d5 yet.} dxc4 ({Otherwise,} 8... Bd6 $5 9.
cxd5 exd5 {transposes to the main line.}) 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 10. Qe2 c5 11. Rfd1 cxd4
12. exd4 (12. Nxd4 {is pretty harmless. Black gets a comfortable game with:} a6
13. Rac1 b5 14. Bb3 {1-0 (61) Gundavaa,B (2501)-Bologan,V (2661) Dubai 2014}
Bc5 15. Be1 Qe7 $11) 12... Rc8 13. Bd3 {[#] This position bears many
similarities to Karpov variation from chapters 5 and 6. Black has a typical
choice at this point:} Bd6 ({or} 13... Bxc3 $5 14. bxc3 Qc7 15. Rac1 Rfe8 16.
Re1 Qd6 $1 17. h3 h6 18. Bb1 $13 {1/2-1/2 (103) Scheeren,P (2445)-Ribli,Z 
(2595) Wijk aan Zee 1983}) 14. Bg5 (14. Nb5 Bb8 15. Bb4 Re8 16. Nd6 Bxd6 17.
Bxd6 Nf8 18. Be5 {1/2-1/2 (20) De Greif,B-Bertholdt,D Munich 1958} Ng6 $15)
14... h6 15. Bh4 Qc7 16. Nb5 Qb8 $11 {1-0 (56) Knaak,R (2535)-Pinter,J (2535)
Zinnowitz 1980 MCL [ChessBase]}) (7. Be2 Bb7 8. O-O Bd6 9. Rc1 a6 10. Qb3 dxc4
11. Qxc4 b5 12. Qb3 Nbd7 $15 {1/2-1/2 (60) Simagin,V-Shamkovich,L Leningrad
1960}) (7. a3 Be7 {transposes to 6.a3.}) 7... exd5 8. Bd3 ({The other move
order to reach the position from the main line is:} 8. Rc1 Bb7 9. Bd3 a6 ({or} 
9... Be7 10. O-O Nbd7) 10. O-O Bd6) 8... Bb7 9. O-O {[#] This position 
(sometimes with Rc1 instead of 0-0) is the tabiya of this variation. White's
plan is to plant the knight on e5 and take it from there. He often supports it
with f2-f4, when a heavy piece lift to the third rank (Pillsbury attack) can
be quite unpleasant for Black. Sometimes, the passive d2-bishop can join the
game via e1-h4. In response to this plan, Black needs to decide how to arrange
his dark-squared bishop and queen's knight (and play ...c7-c5, of course). All
combinations of Bd6/e7 and Nc6/d7 are possible, although 1) Bd6/Nc6 (putting
maximum pressure on d4 and e5) and 2) Be7/Nd7 (preparing Nf6-e4) leave the
best impression, as we will see shortly.} Be7 {It is difficult to say
unequivocally which one of these setups is better. This one seems a bit more
solid} ({than} 9... Bd6 $5 {which leads to a sharper game after:} 10. Rc1 ({
Black does not have to be too concerned with} 10. Nb5 Be7 11. Rc1 {He can
continue with his plan:} c5 12. Ne5 Nbd7 {just ignoring the knight on b5.} ({
Also possible is:} 12... a6 13. Nc3 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Na4 c4
17. Bc2 {1/2-1/2 (33) Tan,Z (2522)-Ju,W (2571) Chongqing/Shanghai 2018} d4 $1
$146 18. exd4 Qxd4 $11) 13. f4 Ne4 $11 {0-1 (46) Gevorgyan,D (2335)-Romanov,E 
(2619) St Petersburg 2016}) 10... a6 11. Ne5 c5 12. f4 Nc6 {[#] This is the
important crossroad for White. He can choose from a big number of interesting
continuations. I have listed them all below, indicating possible improvements
for Black in places:} 13. Ng4 $5 {The idea of this move is to weaken the
defense of d5-pawn by exchanging its main defender.} (13. Ne2 Ne7 14. Ng3 {
0-1 (46) Sandipan,C (2567)-Alekseev,E (2642) St Petersburg 2015} (14. Be1 {
is an inaccurate as it allows Black to accomplish all his goals with:} Ne4 15.
Ng3 cxd4 16. exd4 b5 17. Kh1 f6 {[#] This is pretty much what Black wants to
achieve in this type of position: take control over e4-square and expel white
knight from e5.} 18. Ng4 Qd7 $15 {0-1 (38) Duda,J (2717)-Zhigalko,S (2641)
Katowice 2017}) {and here I would like to recommend:} 14... c4 $5 $146 15. Bb1
b5 {[#] leading to a complex middlegame. For example:} 16. Qf3 a5 17. Be1 Ra6
$5 $13) (13. Be1 cxd4 {[#]} 14. exd4 $5 {This is an interesting pawn sacrifice.
} ({Black is fine once White trades his most active piece:} 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15.
exd4 ({or} 15. Ne2 Bd7 16. Nxd4 Re8 $132 17. Bh4 Rxe3 18. Kh1 Re8 19. Nc6 Bxc6
20. Rxc6 Be7 $15 {0-1 (48) Valenzuela Gomez,F (2389)-Epishin,V (2541) Gijon
ESP 2018}) 15... Re8 16. Bh4 Bf8 $11) 14... Nxd4 15. Bh4 $44 {White has
compensation for the pawn since all his pieces are placed actively.} Ne6 16.
Qf3 Nc5 17. Bb1 Be7 18. Rcd1 {1/2-1/2 (72) Li,C (2720)-Zhigalko,S (2671) Doha
2016 and here Black can force simplifications with:} Nce4 $1 $132 19. Nxe4 dxe4
20. Bxe4 Bxe4 21. Rxd8 Bxf3 22. Rxf8+ Bxf8 23. Rxf3 $11) (13. Na4 {tries to
provoke Black into blocking the center with} c4 {but this is quite
time-consuming and Black gets good play after:} 14. Bb1 b5 15. Nc3 Ne7 16. Qf3
{[#] and now in the game Sandipan,C (2619)-Kazakov,M (2490) Bilbao 2014 1-0 
(33), Black could secure access to e4-square with} Bb4 $1 $132) ({In case of} 
13. Qf3 cxd4 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. exd4 {Black typically obtains counterplay on
the queenside with:} b5 $1 $132 16. f5 b4 17. Ne2 Bb5 $15 {0-1 (53) Koop,T 
(2414)-Roiz,M (2595) Dresden 2015}) 13... Be7 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. dxc5 bxc5 {
[#] This is the position that White was going for. Black hanging pawns look a
bit shaky, so he needs to play carefully over the next few moves. On the other
hand, White has incurred structural weaknesses with f2-f4, which Black may try
to target. Thus, the position is dynamically balanced.} 16. b3 {stopping 16...
c4.} ({Importantly,} 16. Qh5 $2 {fails to:} g6 17. Qxd5 Bxc3 $19) 16... Nb4 17.
Bb1 a5 18. a3 (18. Na4 c4 19. Nc5 Bc6 20. a3 Na6 $11) {All this was played in
Ratkovic,M (2409)-Djordjevic,V (2340) Zrenjanin 2018 ½-½ (106) and now
instead of 18...Na6, I suggest a more dynamic continuation:} 18... d4 $1 $146 {
[#] With this move, Black initiates tactical play in the center and basically
sacrifices his c-pawn. But upsides are that he opens his powerful
light-squared bishop and attacks White's weakest point - the e3-pawn.} 19. Ne4
Nd5 20. Nxf6+ ({In case of} 20. Nxc5 dxe3 21. Nxb7 Qb6 22. Nc5 exd2 23. Qxd2
Rad8 24. Kh1 Rfe8 $132 {Black has excellent play for the pawn.}) 20... Nxf6 21.
Rxc5 Re8 $1 $132 {A strong move. White is not well coordinated and has
difficulties holding the e3-pawn. Perhaps the best solution is to simplify
matters with:} 22. Re5 Rxe5 23. fxe5 Qd5 24. Qf3 dxe3 25. Bxe3 Qxe5 $11) 10.
Rc1 ({Alternatives are:} 10. Ne5 c5 11. f4 Nc6 12. Qf3 cxd4 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14.
exd4 {[#] and here one should remember an important tactical resource:} Ne4 $1
$15 {that was played in 0-1 (28) Schussler,H (2419)-Hammer,J (2632) Sweden
2018 and ½-½ (54) Yu Yangyi (2751)-Wang Hao (2709) Riyadh KSA 2017, giving
Black an instant advantage.}) ({and:} 10. Qc2 Nbd7 (10... c5 $5 11. dxc5 bxc5
12. b3 Na6 $5 {also looks good for Black.} 13. a3 Nc7 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4
16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Bf6 $11) 11. Rfd1 a6 12. Ne5 Re8 13. Ne2 Bd6 $5 (13...
c5 $13) 14. Nc6 Qc8 15. Nf4 g6 16. Rac1 Nb8 17. Ne5 Nbd7 $11 {0-1 (54) Dubov,D
(2666)-Vavulin,M (2507) Kolomna 2016}) 10... Nbd7 {This seems to be the most
accurate move because Black has a good response to 11.Ne5.} ({It is important
to be aware of the following idea for White:} 10... c5 11. Ne5 Nc6 12. Be1 a6
13. f3 $1 {[#] when he activates his dark-squared bishop without weakening
e4-square. The arising symmetrical position is better for White due to
advantage in the activity of Bd3 and b7.} cxd4 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. exd4 Bb7 16.
Bh4 Nh5 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qd2 $14 {1-0 (59) Yu,Y (2759)-Wang,H (2710) Tianjin
2018}) 11. Be1 $1 {This is a relatively new discovery in this line. It may
look very strange at first, but it is actually a useful move considering that
the bishop can be activated via the e1-h4 diagonal after Ne5, f3 or f4.} ({
Another argument in favor of 11.Be1 is that the immediate} 11. Ne5 {can
actually be traded off:} Nxe5 ({There is also nothing wrong with:} 11... c5 12.
f4 {0-1 (41) Bauer,C (2630)-Kryvoruchko,Y (2705) Switzerland 2018} cxd4 $5 $146
13. exd4 Ne4 14. Be3 Ndf6 $13) 12. dxe5 {and after:} Nd7 13. f4 (13. Qc2 g6 14.
e6 Ne5 15. exf7+ Rxf7 $15) 13... Nc5 {[#] Black obtains good counterplay in
the center.} 14. Bb1 {This natural move was played in the only game in this
line, although White has two interesting alternatives.} ({Firstly, all checks
should be checked:} 14. Bxh7+ $5 Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Rf3 {White sets up a
typical attacking battery and now precision is required from Black:} g6 17. Qh6
(17. Rg3 Kg7 18. f5 Rh8 $1 19. Rxg6+ fxg6 20. Qxg6+ Kf8 {[#] White sacrificed
much material to get to this position. However, his attacking attempts are in
vain:} 21. f6 (21. e4 Qe8 $1 22. Bh6+ Rxh6 23. Qxh6+ Kg8 24. Nxd5 Bxd5 25. exd5
Qf8 $17) 21... Bxf6 22. Rf1 Ke7 $1 23. exf6+ Kd7 $17) 17... Bc8 {and now only:}
18. Nxd5 $1 (18. e6 $2 Bxe6 19. Nxd5 Ne4 $1 20. Rc6 Bf6 21. Rxe6 fxe6 22. Qxg6+
Bg7 23. Qxe6+ Rf7 24. Qxe4 c6 $1 $19 {The point.}) {secures a draw after:}
18... Qxd5 19. Bc3 Bf5 20. e6 f6 21. Rh3 Bxh3 22. Qxg6+ Kh8 23. Qh6+ $11) ({
The other alternative is} 14. Be2 {when Black should make sure not to confuse
it with 14.Bb1 and play 14...d4. Instead,} a5 $1 (14... d4 $2 15. Nb5 d3 16.
Bf3 $1 $14 {The point behind 14.Be2.}) 15. Be1 f6 16. exf6 Bxf6 $15 {gives him
a very pleasant position.}) 14... d4 $1 $132 15. Nb5 d3 {[#] Black obtained
nice counterplay in the center. The position is quite complex, with mutual
chances:} 16. Bc3 (16. Nd4 g6 17. Bc3 Qd5 18. Qg4 $13) 16... Qd7 17. Nd4 a5 18.
a3 (18. Bxd3 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 c5 20. Qf5 Qd5 21. Nf3 b5 $132) 18... Rfd8 $132 {
½-½ (37) Idani,P (2583)-Efimenko,Z (2637) Konya 2018}) ({Non-critical
alternatives are:} 11. Ne2 Bd6 12. Ng3 g6 13. Qe2 a6 14. Bc3 Qe7 $11 {0-1 (38)
Sundararajan,K (2445)-Fridman,D (2600) Douglas ENG 2018}) ({and:} 11. Qc2 c5
12. Ne5 c4 13. Bf5 g6 14. Bh3 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. f4 Nc5 17. Ne2 Nd3 $132 {
0-1 (63) Kumar,N (2317)-Gaisinsky,A (1965) Montevideo 2017}) 11... c5 12. Ne5 {
Now, the capture on e5 does not work nearly as well because c5-square is
blocked, so Black makes a preliminary exchange on d4:} cxd4 13. Nxd7 (13. exd4
{allows the aforementioned knight maneuver after:} Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. f4 Nc5
{[#] Similar to 11.Ne5 line, Black obtains good counterplay with this piece
setup, especially once he opens his bishop with ...d5-d4.} 16. Ne2 $6 (16. Nb5
$11) 16... d4 $1 17. Ng3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Qd5 19. Rc2 Rfc8 $17 {1/2-1/2 (52)
Riazantsev,A (2671)-Wojtaszek,R (2749) Doha QAT 2016}) 13... Qxd7 (13... Nxd7 {
is inferior because after:} 14. exd4 Nf6 {White secures an edge with a
well-known motif} 15. f3 $1 {simultaneously protecting e4-square and
activating dark-squared bishop.} g6 16. Bh4 Nh5 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qd2 $14 {
1-0 (32) Fedoseev,V (2703)-Gajewski,G (2628) Khanty-Mansiysk 2017}) 14. Nb5 $1
{This intermediate move is a nice tactical point that keeps the game going.} ({
Instead,} 14. exd4 Ne4 15. f3 Nxc3 16. Rxc3 Rac8 $11 {is totally dry.}) 14...
Rfc8 15. Rxc8+ Rxc8 16. Nxd4 g6 {[#] White obtained a slight moral advantage
by forcing Black into a position with an isolated pawn. However, GM Nigel
Short has proven that it is easy to hold the balance:} 17. f3 Ne8 $5 {Black
initiates an interesting knight maneuver to d6.} (17... a6 18. Bc3 Bd6 $11 {
is more standard.}) 18. Bb5 (18. Bc3 Nd6 19. Ne2 Bg5 20. Bd4 Qe7 $132) 18...
Qd8 19. Bxe8 Qxe8 20. Bc3 Ba6 21. Re1 Bh4 22. g3 Be7 23. Ne2 Bb7 24. Nf4 Qb5
25. Qd4 f6 26. Rd1 Kf7 27. Qd3 Qxd3 28. Rxd3 Rc5 29. Kf2 g5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (34)
Sandipan,C (2573)-Short,N (2656) Kolkata 2018} *

