{[%evp 0,7,20,20,20,-11,-11,-11,26,-10]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 {
[#] This is a very rare system, but it leads to slightly different positions
to those that we have analyzed in main variations of the Nimzo-Indian, so it
is worth taking a closer look at it. The most logical reply is} c5 {
simultaneously defending the bishop and attacking d4-pawn.} 5. dxc5 ({Rare
alternatives are:} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. e3 (6. dxc5 {- 5.dxc5}) 6... cxd4 7. exd4 d5
8. Bg5 O-O {[#] After the exchange of c- and d-pawns, Black will get a good
version of IQP middlegame.} 9. Rd1 (9. Be2 dxc4 10. Qxc4 Be7 11. O-O Nd5 12.
Bxe7 Ncxe7 $11) 9... h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Be2 dxc4 12. Qxc4 Bxc3+ 13. Qxc3 Bd7
14. Ne5 Rfd8 15. O-O Rac8 16. Bf3 Be8 $15 {0-1 (47) Bellon Lopez,J (2445)
-Macieja,B (2612) Barbera del Valles 2009}) ({and:} 5. d5 $6 O-O 6. Bg5 exd5 $1
7. cxd5 d6 {[#] which pretty much transposes to Chapter 20 with move Qb3,
which does not seem useful for White.} 8. e3 ({White seriously lagged in
development after:} 8. e4 h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Bd3 Qg6 11. g3 f5 $1 12. exf5
Bxf5 $36 {K.Spicak-M.Grabarczyk, Warsaw 1997}) 8... Nbd7 9. Nf3 h6 10. Bh4 {
Instead of Qa5, Black has another way to attack the d5-pawn:} Nb6 11. Rd1 Bd7
$1 $17 {threatening to trap the queen with 12...Ba4!}) 5... Nc6 $1 {This is an
important point. Black does not hurry to retrieve the pawn, but rather focuses
on development. This gives him additional options, such as ...Nf6-e4, Qa5, etc.
White has several reasonable options at this point. The most common one is} 6.
Bg5 ({In case of} 6. Nf3 {Black can use the pin to play} Ne4 $5 {and force a
positional concession from White.} 7. Bd2 {White surrenders the bishop pair.
Otherwise, he would be saddled with a poor pawn structure.} Nxd2 8. Nxd2 Bxc5 {
[#] Since White firmly controls ...d7-d5 break, Black will have to develop his
bishop via b7. With that in mind,} 9. g3 {makes the most sense to create
opposition to the light-squared bishop.} ({In case of} 9. e3 {Black can cover
e4-square first, with} f5 $5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O b6 12. a3 Bb7 {[#] and having
completed his development, Black has good chances in this position.} 13. Qc2
Rc8 14. Bf3 f4 $1 $36 {0-1 (35) Pakleza,Z (2483)-Wojtaszek,R (2635) Warsaw 2007
}) ({White can also play} 9. Nde4 Be7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. e3 ({although there is
no point in putting the knight on} 11. Nd6 $6 {without developing first, due
to:} Na5 12. Qa4 Qb6 $36) 11... Qc7 12. Be2 f5 13. Nb5 Qe5 14. Nd2 {This was
played in the game Konovalov,N (2424)-Krivoborodov,E (2514) Moscow 2012 ½-½ 
(50), when I suggest the following way to complete development:} a6 $5 $146 15.
Nf3 Qb8 16. Nc3 b6 17. O-O Qc7 $13) 9... b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O O-O {[#] This
looks like a position from Queen's Indian defense. Black should not be facing
difficulties in this roughly equal position, especially if he gets to trade
light-squared bishops.} 12. a3 (12. Rac1 Be7 (12... Rc8 13. Qc2 Be7 14. Rfd1
Qc7 {Queen is exposed here and White takes advantage of it with:} 15. Nde4 a6
16. Nd5 exd5 17. cxd5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (70) Aczel,G (2567)-Gavrilescu,D (2436)
Timisoara 2018}) 13. Qc2 Qb8 {This is the right square for the queen.} 14. Rfd1
Rd8 (14... Nb4 $5 {also deserves attention, aiming for the type of position
from Adhiban's game:} 15. Qb1 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 f5 $132) 15. a3 a6 $13) 12... f5
13. e3 Qc8 14. Qd1 Ne5 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 {[#] and Black has a comfortable position.
Adhiban took the initiative after:} 16. Qe2 Rac8 17. b4 Be7 18. Rfc1 a5 $1 19.
Rab1 axb4 20. axb4 g5 $1 21. Nb5 g4 22. Nd4 Ra8 $36 {0-1 (50) Lorscheid,G 
(2214)-Adhiban,B (2663) Stockholm 2016}) (6. a3 {forces Black to take} Bxc5 7.
Nf3 (7. Bg5 $4 Bxf2+ $1 {is a well-known opening trick.}) 7... O-O 8. Bg5 (8.
Bf4 {allows} d5 {leading to a QGD with somewhat misplaced queen on b3.}) {
and here I like the following simplification maneuver:} 8... Nd4 $5 {[#] This
is a well-known idea from 4.Qc2 c5 Nimzo-Indian, but here it works even better
for Black due to far from an ideal position of white queen.} 9. Nxd4 Bxd4 10.
e3 (10. O-O-O Bxc3 $1 11. Qxc3 Ne4 $1 12. Bxd8 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Rxd8 14. c5 b6 15.
c6 Ba6 16. cxd7 Bb5 $15) 10... Qa5 $1 {This is the point. Black forces trade
of dark-squared bishops and this leads to a roughly equal position after:} 11.
exd4 Qxg5 12. g3 d5 13. Bg2 dxc4 14. Qxc4 Bd7 $1 $11 15. Bxb7 $6 Rab8 16. Qa6
$2 e5 $1 17. O-O exd4 18. Ne4 Qb5 $1 $19 {0-1 (29) Konovalov,N (2426)-Zhigalko,
A (2545) Minsk 2008}) 6... h6 ({In his book on the Nimzo-Indian defense,
grandmaster John Emms suggests the following interesting pawn sacrifice:} 6...
b6 $5 $146 {[#] A similar idea will be seen in 6...h6 variation. Black opens
files on the queenside, where he has an advantage in numbers. Black obtains
good counterplay, as we can see from the following variations:} 7. cxb6 (7. e3
bxc5 8. Nf3 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Ne4 $132) (7. a3 Ba5 8. cxb6 Qxb6 9. Qxb6
Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 axb6 $44) 7... Qxb6 {8...Ne4 is a strong threat, thus:} 8. Bxf6
gxf6 9. e3 (9. a3 $2 {runs into some nice tactical shots:} Nd4 $1 10. Qd1 Bxc3+
11. bxc3 Qb2 $1 12. Rc1 Nb3 13. Rc2 Qxa3 $17) 9... Rb8 10. Nf3 Na5 11. Qc2
Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qb2 13. Qxb2 Rxb2 14. Nd2 Ba6 15. Kd1 Ke7 $36 {with initiative
in the endgame.}) 7. Bxf6 (7. Bh4 {allows:} g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. e3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3
{1-0 (31) Botvinnik,M-Ragozin,V Leningrad 1932 and now simply:} Nxc5 $146 11.
Qc2 d6 12. h4 g4 13. Ne2 e5 $1 $15 {leads to a positional advantage for Black.}
) 7... Qxf6 8. Nf3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 10. bxc3 b6 $1 {[#] The key idea in
these positions. Black obtains excellent counterplay down the a-file, when
White can hardly count on anything more than a draw with such a terrible pawn
structure.} 11. cxb6 axb6 $44 12. e3 (12. e4 Ra4 $11 ({another good
possibility is} 12... Na5 $5 13. Nd2 Ke7 14. Be2 Ba6) 13. Bd3 Ba6 14. Kd2 Bxc4
15. Bxc4 Rxc4 16. Kd3 Ra4 17. Rhb1 Ra6 18. Nd2 Ke7 19. Nc4 Rb8 20. a4 b5 {
1/2-1/2 (20) Gofshtein,L (2520)-Har Zvi,R (2510) Israel 1998}) 12... Ke7 13.
Be2 Ra4 14. O-O Ba6 15. Nd2 Ne5 16. Rfb1 Nxc4 17. Bxc4 Bxc4 18. Nxc4 Rxc4 19.
Rxb6 Rxc3 20. Rb2 Rhc8 21. h4 Rc1+ {1/2-1/2 (21) Varga,Z (2515)-Almasi,Z (2628)
Kazincbarcika 2005} *

